(5012,E'10110 Flying Cloud Dr',E'Eden Prairie',E'MN',55347,NULL,NULL,E'Flying Cloud Airport control tower',E'Unknown',E'1963',E'Acquired in 1941 to train Navy Pilots, Navy planes stationed at old Wold-Chamberlain Field used the strip to make practice approaches; when the Navy no no longer needed the field, it was sold to private development and originally planned as “Southwest Minneapolis Airport” before shifting to a name that combined both local Indian lore and flying; sold to the Metropolitan Airports Commission (MAC) in 1948; MAC paved the runway the next year built the control tower; in 1966, the airport ranked second only to Chicago’s O’Hare Airport as the busiest field in the central United States.'),
