(5052,E'851 30th Ave SE',E'Rochester',E'MN ',55904,NULL,NULL,E'Rochester State Junior College',E'Haarstick, Lundgren & Assoc.',E'1969-71',E'Received an Award of Merit from the 1970 Community and Junior College Design Awards, which recognized "distinguished college projects which provide creative and inspired responses to educational program criteria and community needs." The awards were presented at the 50th annual convention of the American Association of Junior Colleges, and were co-sponsor by the AIA, Educational Facilities Laboratories, Inc., and the Office of Construction Services of the Office of Education of the US Department of Health, Education and Welfare and published in the March 1970 issue of the AIA Journal. For this project, the jury noted: "A highly expressive building form, well reflecting the activities housed within. Significant is the appropriate fitting of the buildings into the site. The strong, bold brick forms and skillful use of brick planes and openings provide dramatic and exciting spaces and are highly reflective of the educational program. Most commendable is the care and handling of major and minor concepts and the achievement of continuity throughout." Minneapolis-based firm assigned in 1969 to design the new campus a junior college founded in 1915; by 2020 the school was named Rochester Community and Technical College.'),
(5053,E'11200 Mississippi Blvd',E'Coon Rapids',E'MN',55433,NULL,NULL,E'Anoka-Ramsey Community College',E'Cerny Associates',E'1967',NULL),
(5054,E'3401 E County Line N',E'White Bear Lake ',E'MN',55110,NULL,NULL,E'Lakewood State Junior College',E'Grover Dimond Assoc.',E'1969-72',E'The phased construction was noted in the May 1969 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism): To account for the cold climate, the campus was designed as a megastructure concept to provide a climate-controlled environment for students moving between classes; it was designed as 4 interconnected elements, sited to face south; it was planned to be built in a rapid series of phases: the 1st three-story phase (92,000sqft) housed administration, library, and exhibition areas, computer facilities for the entire 18-unit state junior college system, and classrooms for the departments of practical arts, science, and humanities; the 2nd phase (scheduled for summer 1970) was the activities section; the 3rd phase was a humanities element equal in size to the first section (summer of 1972) then finally an fine arts section with theater (planned for 1973). Founded in 1967 as part of the state\'s junior college building boom; In 1996 merged with Northeast Metro Technical College to become Century College.'),
(5055,E'7411 85th Ave N',E'Brooklyn Park',E'MN',55445,NULL,NULL,E'North Hennepin Junior College',E'Matson & Wegleitner ',E'1968-70',E'Founded in 1966 as part of the state\'s junior college building boom; later renamed North Hennepin Community College.'),
(5056,E'9700 France Ave S',E'Bloomington ',E'MN',55431,NULL,NULL,E'Normandale State Junior College',E'Ellerbe & Co.',E'1967-68',E'Later renamed Normandale Community College; In 1970, the Bloomington Affliated Garden Clubs funded the creation of a traditional Japanese garden designed by Takao Watanabe, a landscape architect with the Tokyo metropolitan department of parks, and built from 1972-75; 1974-75 add\'n by Hodne/Stageberg: a $2.4M structure adding science facilities, student center, and bookstore on the top floor.'),
