(5067,E'703 Emerson Ave N',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55411,NULL,NULL,E'Cecil Newman Plaza',E'Adkins-Jackels Associates',E'1969-70',E'Part of the Grant Park urban renewal area that was developed from 1967-72; after some competition, the development was divided between projects by the Residents\' Committee for Bethune Development (Parkview Apartments designed by Lorenzo D. Williams) and by Midwest Improvement Co. (City View apartments and Cecil Newman Plaza, designed by Adkins-Jackels); Named in honor of a newspaper editor and black community leader, the project was conceived and carried through by the Midwest Improvement Assoc.; 64 units of 1, 2, and 3-bedrooms; a second phase planned of efficiencies, then a third phase of 120 units for senior citizens planned for 1972; Builder: First Minnesota Const. Co.'),
(5068,E'4913 Coventry Rd W',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55345,NULL,NULL,E'Robert & Jean Mason Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Builder\'s own house (possibly own design, mixed with an existing plan), Robert H. Mason\'s rustic contemporary home was featured in a 1962 Minneapolis Tribune article on the homes owned by home builders: "has the convenience and clean lines of contemporary styling. But the cedar-shake siding on the exterior [...] gives the home a warm feeling. The all-purpose family room [...] about which the house is centered, has easy access to the kitchen area, the dining area, the patio, and the stone entry."'),
(5069,E'6401 Penn Ave S',E'Richfield',E'MN',55423,NULL,NULL,E'Richfield Fire Station No. 2',E'Shimer, Ralph B.',E'1963',E'Builder: W.C. Borrensen Const. Co.; underwent major face-lift/revamp in 2012 ($900k), although the rear facade remains the same.'),
(5070,E'2201 108th St W',E'Bloomington ',E'MN',55431,NULL,NULL,E'Nine Mile Elementary School',E'Armstrong & Schlichting',E'1961-62',E'The hexagonal design was intended to blend into the wooded site and require as little tree-cutting as possible: three classroom on each side with windows toward the outside, with the offices and gym-auditorium in the center and lit with translucent domes; the 2 hexagonal annexes contain the kindergarten as well as the lunchroom and kitchen; Builder: Adolfson & Peterson; estimated total cost was $584,423; sold c.1984 to be come the Bloomington Church of God.'),
