(5094,E'2040 Merrihills Dr SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Drs. Charles H. & Ursula G. McKenna Residence',E'Unknown',E'1966',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, flat-roof house featuring vertical wood-siding. At the time of construction, the McKennas were physicians at the Mayo Clinic: Charles in Internal Medicine and Rheumatology; Ursula in Internal Medicine.'),
(5095,E'2025 Merrihills Dr SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. Deloran L. & Edith L. Thurber Residence',E'Unknown',E'1964',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, rambler with tuck-under garage on the short side. At the time of construction, Dr. Del Thurber (1929-2020) was a physician with the Mayo Clinic; he did his residency at Mayo Clinic as a resident in 1958, specialized in tetanus, and retired as an internist in Community Medicine in 1991.'),
(5096,E'2404 Balsam Ct SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. William P. & Eleanor T. Baldus Residence',E'Unknown',E'1965',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, flat roof house featuring vertical wood-siding and clerestory windows. At the time of construction, Baldrus was a physician (gastroenterology) with the Mayo Clinic.'),
(5097,E'2605 Crest Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. Hugo S. & Joan Raimundo Residence',E'Unknown',E'1965',E'Rambler with stone exterior, backing against a creek at the edge of the Merrihills neighborhood. At the time of construction, Raimundo was a physician (anesthesiology) and Joan was a nurse with the Mayo Clinic.'),
(5098,E'2400 Crest Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. & Mrs. Gunnar B. Stickler Residence',E'Stageberg, James',E'1964',E'Received an Honorable Mention in the 1965 AIA MN Awards. Hill-top parcel in Merrihills neighborhood, featuring dramatic clerestory windows and shed roofs. There are multiple outside decks on all sides (as all sides feature views). The 2,150sf house is all wood framing, plastered inside and blown-on stucco outside. The clients were a couple originally from Bavaria with two children, wanted a house in character with their background on what was a 3-acre wooded suburban lot with the best view to the northwest. In his own remarks on the design, Stageberg noted "The solution provides some elegant interior spaces within a simple shell. The pitched parts of the roof occur over the living room, kitchen, study and master bedroom. The dining room and entry overlook the living room and the northwest view." The 1965 jury met in MIT\'s Dept. of Architecture and, giving the house an Honorable Mention, remarked: "A simple, straightforward house well adapted to site, with interesting interior space and detail. The pitched parts of the roof and some of the fenestration seem rather arbitrary relative to the plan." Total cost was $34,000 in 1966. Stickler was a pediatrician who made substantial contributions to the field of pediatrics, including being the first scientist to describe a hereditary condition now known as Stickler syndrome; he retired in 1989 and died unexpectedly from stroke in 2010 at his home in Wayzata. Prior to moving into the house, Stickler lived in the temporary housing the Mayos created in the Mayo Homestead Addition (specifically the house at 1406 Damon Ct).'),
(5099,E'2505 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1968',E'Looks similar to Stageberg\'s works (particularly in University Grove) with vertical wood, flat roof, and dramatic rounded sections with window slits.'),
(5100,E'2409 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. John A. & Rena Y. Dyer Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, featuring covered walkway between garage and house; hipped roof at a low pitch. Fairly open floorplan. At the time of construction, Dyer (1923-2010) was a physician (Ophthalmology) with the Mayo Clinic; he began as a fellow in the specialty in 1953, joining the staff as a Consultant of Ophthalmology in 1956, and rose to the rank of Professor in Mayo Medical School.'),
(5101,E'2401 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. Philip E. & Marilyn J. Bernatz Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Modern X-shaped ranch house in the Merrihills neighborhood; wood siding with vertical accents; low pitch gable roof; a breezeway/patio between the garage and house may have been converted into interior space c. 2012. At the time of construction, Bernatz (1921-2010) was an internationally noted physician and thoracic surgeon with the Mayo Clinic. After WW2 he joined the surgery residency program at the Mayo Clinic and Mayo Graduate School of Medicine, pursuing subspecialty fellowship training in thoracic surgery, and was appointed to the consulting staff at Mayo in 1955; he developed the "Bernatz Classification" histopathologic categorization of thymoma. '),
(5102,E'2402 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Otto W. & Ingrid Ritter Residence',E'Unknown',E'1969',E'Modern ranch house in the Merrihills development with a slight banana-shape and stone siding with vertical redwood; interesting roof overhangs over entrance pathway alongside the house. Ritter was a manager for IBM.'),
(5103,E'2316 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. John Mayne Residence',E'Stageberg, James',E'1965',E'Featured in a Minneapolis Tribune article (06/19/1966), the design process began when Dr. Mayne found the site on a former orchard in the new Merrihills neighborhood that featured a view of the downtown Rochester skyline; he wanted to preserve the apple trees on the lot. Stageberg visited the site 5 times, including at night to get a sense of the views. With careful siting and contour preservation, the split-level house only led to the removal of 4 of approximately 30 trees on site. Stageberg noted "Living close to trees in a house with a large expanse of glass gives a person more of the feeling of the change of seasons. And trees never have an ugly moment. Even in wintertime an apple tree has a wonderful, gnarled shape." The long house (55\'x28\') is all brick with exposed redwood beams and what was originally a wood roof; the entry has a covered canopy and the roof has long overhangs; the architect noted "We wanted to retain the natural qualities of the site so it seemed advisable to use natural materials . . . clay and wood." An attached garage was added to the north side of the house, the addition is sympathetic and the owner reported that Stageberg approved. Mayne was a consultant in internal medicine at the Mayo Clinic. Later sold to Dr. Edward Didier, an anesthesiologist who was part of a team of 7 Mayo doctors assembled at the request of First Lady Nancy Reagan to operate on President Ronald Reagan at Bethesda Naval Medical Center in 1987.'),
(5104,E'2305 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. Richard H. Ferguson Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Modern ranch house in the Merrihills development with vertical redwood siding and a covered walking path to the main door with posts. At the time of construction, Ferguson (1924-2007) was a physician with the Mayo Clinic; his association began when he was a fellow in residency from 1951-54, then after military service, returned as a consulting physician at Mayo Clinic from 1959 until his retirement, including serving as head of a Section of Rheumatology (1966-76), and serving as a professor starting in 1979, and as a member of the Mayo Clinic Board of Governors from 1976-84.'),
(5105,E'2220 Hillside Ln SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. James A. & Louis L. Bastron Residence',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Large, modern ranch house in the Merrihills development with stucco siding and wood accents that give it a vaguely Japanese influence; low-pitched hip roof. At the time of construction, Bastron (1920-2014) was a physician (neurology) with the Mayo Clinic; his association began in 1948, when he entered the Mayo Graduate School of Medicine, was named an Assistant to Staff in 1951, appointed Consultant in Neurology; he became an instructor in the Mayo Graduate School of Medicine from 1956-67, and advanced to Assistant Professor of Neurology in 1973, retiring in 1985 and becoming Medical Director of the U.S. Bureau of Prison\'s Federal Medical Center in Rochester.'),
(5106,E'2122 Balsam Ct SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. Cameron G. Strong Residence',E'Unknown',E'1967',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, Part low mansard roof, part low-pitch hip roof house featuring vertical redwood-siding. Secluded site. At the time of construction, Strong (1934-2009) had just returned to the staff and faculty Mayo Clinic and Mayo Medical School, where he practiced internal medicine and nephrology; he later served as chair of the Division of Nephrology and subsequently as chair of the Division of Hypertension of Mayo Clinic, as well as the Mayo Board of Trustees.'),
(5107,E'1935 Westwood Ct SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1966',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, flat roof, austere wood exterior with large windows; secluded culdesac lot.'),
(5108,E'2808 Merrihills Dr SW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55902,NULL,NULL,E'Drs. J. Aiden & F.M.T. Carney Residence',E'Unknown',E'1967',E'Modern house in the Merrihills development, steep mansard with cut-out for some dramatic 2-story windows. At the time of construction, the Carneys were physicians at the Mayo Clinic: Francoise (1935-81) in the Department of Anesthesiology, Aiden (b. 1934) in pathology. Aiden is best known for describing what became known as Carney syndrome, the separate phenomenon of Carney\'s triad, and Carney-Stratakis syndrome; Aiden retired in 2018. '),
