(5155,E'508 Humboldt Ave',E'St Paul',E'MN',55107,NULL,NULL,E'Senior Apartments (Wilder Humboldt Campus)',E'Rapson, Ralph',E'1962-63',E'Received AIA MN Award of Merit (1963); recognized with Award of Merit for design excellence by the Community Facilities Administration\'s 1964 Design Awards Program. Featured in the May 1967 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism); Pair of apartment buildings designed for low-income seniors who are still self-sufficient (but find an elevator easier than stairs); Rapson faced a program that called for non-institutional, residential quality on a very low budget, thus used a unique structural system and inexpensive materials: structural engineer Donald Olson devised a way to make the most efficient use of steel and concrete (basically: concrete columns with rebar to hold steel beams); Rapson then used dark brick to contrast with the natural concrete block to give buildings a quiet residential character. Cost (2 buildings): $1,029,467; Associates: Richard Morrill, Kay Lockhart; Landscape architect: Charles Wood; Structural Engineer: Donald Olsen; Mechanical/electrical engineer: Gausman & Moore, Inc.; Builder: James Steele Const. Co. Part of what was the Wilder Humboldt Campus; developed as affordable housing for seniors of moderate income by the Amherst H. Wilder Foundation (St. Paul), founded by railroad/lumber fortunes, the mission of which is "To promote the social welfare of persons resident or located in the greater Saint Paul metropolitan area by all appropriate means." The buildings were sold in 2013 when finances tightened at the organization.'),
(5156,E'510 Humboldt Ave',E'St Paul',E'MN',55107,NULL,NULL,E'Senior Apartments (Wilder Humboldt Campus)',E'Rapson, Ralph',E'1962-63',E'Received AIA MN Award of Merit (1963); recognized with Award of Merit for design excellence by the Community Facilities Administration\'s 1964 Design Awards Program. Featured in the May 1967 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism); Pair of apartment buildings designed for low-income seniors who are still self-sufficient (but find an elevator easier than stairs); Rapson faced a program that called for non-institutional, residential quality on a very low budget, thus used a unique structural system and inexpensive materials: structural engineer Donald Olson devised a way to make the most efficient use of steel and concrete (basically: concrete columns with rebar to hold steel beams); Rapson then used dark brick to contrast with the natural concrete block to give buildings a quiet residential character. Cost (2 buildings): $1,029,467; Associates: Richard Morrill, Kay Lockhart; Landscape architect: Charles Wood; Structural Engineer: Donald Olsen; Mechanical/electrical engineer: Gausman & Moore, Inc.; Builder: James Steele Const. Co. Part of what was the Wilder Humboldt Campus; developed as affordable housing for seniors of moderate income by the Amherst H. Wilder Foundation (St. Paul), founded by railroad/lumber fortunes, the mission of which is "To promote the social welfare of persons resident or located in the greater Saint Paul metropolitan area by all appropriate means." The buildings were sold in 2013 when finances tightened at the organization.'),
