(5161,E'1805 Innsbruck Pkwy',E'Fridley',E'MN',55421,NULL,NULL,E'1964 World\'s Fair House (Formica House; French Provincial)',E'Schmidlin, Emil A.',E'1964',E'Builder/Developer: Rodney W. Billman; Originally priced at $37,500, its primary national sponsor was Formica (which sponsored the entire program; it\'s cabinetry was featured) and its local sponsor was Northern States Power Co. (for being a totally electric home); the original design was by New Jersey-based architect Emil A. Schmidlin (d. 1988) and available in 6 styles, it was modified by local designer John A. Kinsell to conform with the corner lot and also meet local weather conditions; this house was touted for featuring "Radiant overhead electric heat with thermostat in each room," "Dow Styrofoam insulated basement walls," "Acrylite skydomes, room dividers and shower doors," "Unique lighting fixtures in this official Light-for-Living home," "Formica cabinets and wood-grain paneling." '),
(5162,E'1766 Maple Ln',E'Roseville',E'MN',55113,NULL,NULL,E'1964 World\'s Fair House (Formica House; Split-Level)',E'Schmidlin, Emil A.',E'1964',E'Builder/Developer: Midland Const. Co.; Originally priced at $37,500, its primary national sponsor was Formica (which sponsored the entire program; it\'s cabinetry was featured) and its local sponsor was Northern States Power Co. (for being a totally electric home); the original design was by New Jersey-based architect Emil A. Schmidlin (d. 1988) and available in 6 styles, it was modified by local designers; this version looks very heavily adapted by designer Robert C. Olson, as none of the models in the 6 models in the official brochure appeared to be a split-level, however it was sponsored by Formica; '),
