(5165,E'10530 Mississippi Blvd NW',E'Coon Rapids',E'MN',55433,NULL,NULL,E'Gordon K. Peterson Residence',E'Unknown',E'1963',E'Organic design with overhanging eaves that make the house almost appear like a bug from the aerial view; has similarly designed guest house above a detached garage; Property has its own boat launch ramp descending from the north side of the house.'),
(5166,E'2330 Innsbruck Pkwy',E'Columbia Heights',E'MN',55421,NULL,NULL,E'1967 Wood for Living Award #1',E'Rodney W. Billman, Builder',E'1967',E'Builder: Rodney W. Billman; One of five houses in the Twin Cities awarded "for effective use of quality wood products in homes constructed with the builders\' own designs" by the Wood Marketing, Inc., a national organization sponsored by large wood and lumber companies. The home definitely uses wood shingle and redwood beams to create an interesting design.'),
(5167,E'4908 Heritage Hills Dr',E'Bloomington ',E'MN',55437,NULL,NULL,E'1967 Wood for Living Award #2',E'Hirsh Bros., Builder',E'1967',E'Builder: Hirsch Bros., Inc.; One of five houses in the Twin Cities awarded "for effective use of quality wood products in homes constructed with the builders\' own designs" by the Wood Marketing, Inc., a national organization sponsored by large wood and lumber companies. U-shaped house with a dramatic entry through courtyard; exposed rustic beams, curver stairway, wood ceiling in the family room, food-framed glass doors to patio.'),
(5168,E'4400 98th Street Cir W',E'Bloomington ',E'MN',55437,NULL,NULL,E'1967 Wood for Living Award #4',E'Marvin H. Anderson, Builder',E'1967',E'Builder: Marvin H. Anderson; Builder: One of five houses in the Twin Cities awarded "for effective use of quality wood products in homes constructed with the builders\' own designs" by the Wood Marketing, Inc., a national organization sponsored by large wood and lumber companies. 3-level contemporary with 5-bed, 3-bath, living room with walnut paneling, exposed-beam ceiling and wood windows.'),
(5169,E'5316 Matterhorn Dr NE',E'Fridley',E'MN',55421,NULL,NULL,E'Total Electric Home (1960)',E'Rodney W. Billman, Builder',E'1960',E'Promoted by a several organizations. first as one of 5 all-electric home promoted as a "Total Electric Home" (Gold Medallion Home) by Northern States Power Co. for being one of the first homes with all-year electric climate control (electric heating, AC, humidity control, air purification, air circulation) ; it was promoted as being an all-electric home using Hotpoint appliances; It was one of two model homes featuring “full insulation and housepower wiring of the nationally-promoted comfort conditioned home” program of Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp.'),
(5170,E'1133 Kenwood Pkwy',E'Minneapolis ',E'MN',55403,NULL,NULL,E'Part of the Franz & Jane Gayl Residence',E'Gayl, Franz J.R.',E'1964',E'This structure began with a section of a German-born architect\'s own house and a unique saga: Franz spotted a shed near the University of Minnesota (where he was studying architecture) and bought it for $15; during this time he met Carleton student Jane Hauser (a future computer programmer whose father was an honorary German consul) and the two were engaged; when walking from Jane\'s family house in Kenwood to Plymouth Congregational Church, they saw a difficult, steep lot with potential and bought it to build the house they would move into after they married; they started by moving the shed to the lot in August 1951, then the couple began building the foundation/walk-out basement toward the street. The process garnered two separate newspaper features: 09/30/51 (Minneapolis Tribune) about the initial construction, 05/22/60 (The Minneapolis Star ) about how architects create interesting houses with difficult lots (plus the addition the built); Franz said he "used everything in the book" to safeguard the house he built on a slope in Lowry Hill; to safeguard against seepage and slippage; Franz said he and his wife "had to excavate three times as much gravel and sand overlay as we expected to get down to solid earth" when they began putting in the foundation for their converted shed home; the could dug it themselves, as no company would send machines to do it it for fear of starting a landslide; they buttressed the rear retaining wall with 16" horizontal and 12" lateral reinforcements; Franz said "We laid four-inch drain tile around three sides and filled in with crushed rock and gravel. Mastic coating was applied to the exterior of the backwalls. Maybe we went overboard a little, but we haven\'t had to wipe up a drop of water." Digging for the water main was fiasco because the city map was wrong (the city compensated them for the extra work). The 1951 article had photos of the wild design, under construction, with the then-engaged couple  still working on the natural cedar siding house; they had a traditional German house-raising ceremony, a Richtfest. In 1959 they doubled the size of their house by adding a living-room, two bedrooms add a bath in a side addition. The street was obliterated by the construction of I-94 in the 1960s; when it existed, Forest Ave ran parallel and just to the north of Ridgewood Ave, which is now (2020) where I-94 emerges from the Lowry Tunnel. By 1964 the Gayls bought an island on Lake Minnetonka and Franz\'s first plan was to move this house by barge; however they were “outbid” and opted to build a new house, while a section of this house (roughly matching the size of the \'59 addition) was moved on  September 10, 1964 to a new foundation built at 1133 Kenwood Pkwy in a vaguely similar topography (on the side of a steep hill); by 2020 the home still shows modern, but may be fundamentally a different house (with a new glass entry on the east side), though influenced by Gayl. It seems best to date this house to date of the move.'),
(5171,E'4701 40th St W',E'St Louis Park',E'MN',55416,NULL,NULL,E'Crooked House',E'Gellert, Gene',E'1960',E'Designed without a square corner, the builder and co-designer Leslie R. Johnson described it as "my version of the future trend in housing." The $33K house was built on a sharply triangular lot, the experienced builder struggled to find an architect who understood what he wanted until Gellert (the 6th he spoke to); the solution was a massive-looking split-level set closely to the base of the triangle and tapering toward a large fireplace at the apex; the exterior is Arizona crab orchard stone and cedar; the lower level has a living room with cathedral ceiling and dining room, but the kitchen is upstairs (via an open, ornamental stairway); there are no 90-degree corners.'),
(5172,E'730 Big Island',E'Orono',E'MN',55331,NULL,NULL,E'Franz & Jane Gayl Residence II',E'Gayl, Franz J.R.',E'1964',E'Architect\'s own house. After the long saga of the German-born architect\'s original home on 327 Forest Ave (the street was destroyed by freeway construction) "He wanted a place where no freeway would ever bother him again." Franz wanted to live in the wilderness but his wife, Jane (nee Hauser), wanted to be near the city. The compromise was a  2.79 acres island in Lake Minnetonka that was cut from Big Island by a channel created by a previous owner.  After buying it, Jane mapped the island and the couple successfully petitioned to name the island Mahpiyata, after a Lakota princess that Jane found in Minnetonka legend. His original plan was to move the Forest Ave house by barge, but he was out-bid for the remaining section of the house (that was moved to 1133 Kenwood); to build the new house, he bought an Army surplus DUKW (aka a Duck, the 6-wheeled amphibious vehicle) to ferry building materials to the island, using a portable generating plant for electricity; his plan was to use the DUKW and a propeller-driven snow sled to get to and from the house to the mainland.  The house itself was designed with 3 bedrooms, a den, and 1 bath on the downstairs, and a kitchen, living, dining, and library upstairs; Gayl said it "isn\'t meant to be any particular style, it is the simplest structure possible, the least obtrusive, to disturb the natural surroundings as little as possible." At the time, Gayl was an architectural designer for Minnegasco, and Jane was a computer programmer who worked for Northwestern Bell, Univac, and General Mills (where she helped program the company\'s first mainframe computer system). The couple divorced in 1968.'),
(5173,E'1000 44th Ave N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Apollo High School',E'Traynor, Hermanson & Hahn',E'1969-70',E'Named in 1969 to honor the Apollo 11 moon mission; the campus was sprawled on a 64-acre property, the 325,000 sq ft building was designed as a 1-story structure because it was more cost effective on cheap land (the property was federal surplus land bought for $1200); the reddish brown brick structure was designed for 2000 students and 100 teachers, giving each teacher an office;  it included a 900-seat theater, TV studio, library with 15,000 books; to save money, a man-made lake was built in the SE corner to supply earth for other parts of the building (saving $100k); the resulting pond was to be used by the biology dept. and was named the Sea of Tranquility to continue the Apollo mission theme.'),
(5174,E'320 Fifth Ave SE',E'Melrose',E'MN',56352,NULL,NULL,E'St. Mary\'s Catholic School',E'Pinault, Louis C.',E'1964',NULL),
(5175,E'303 5th St N',E'Breckenridge',E'MN',56520,NULL,NULL,E'Joseph Vertin & Sons Funeral Home',E'Siddens, Virgil E.',E'1961',E'Brick, horizontal form with flat roof; looks to be in good shape as of 2018.'),
(5176,E'402 7th Ave N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Cathedral High School North Gymnasium',E'Pinault-Truszinski & Co.',E'1965-66',E'The $650,000 facility was funded by the diocesan New Horizon\'s campaign ($500k) and the 13 parishes in the school board ($150k); the two-story structure is on a hillside, with the full height only visible from the east but the main entrance on the west; the steel-and-concrete building has a light brick exterior facade, with local granite accenting the entrance; Builder: Wahl Const.; In 2020 a new 32,000-square-foot building was built in the parking lot between the old center building and the north gymnasium to connect the two and expand the shcool.'),
(5177,E'1009 6th Ave N',E'Sauk Rapids',E'MN',56379,NULL,NULL,E'Pleasantview Elementary School',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1969-70',E'The $1.5M building designed in three nearly round pods (nonagons); all the classrooms in each pod are open and built around a center consisting of a large media center serves as a library, AV and resource center in which students may work independently; the side-by-side classrooms were designed to be controlled by acoustics (see roof design), the idea was to encourage team teaching. Firm became Traynor, Hermanson & Hahn during construction (May 1969). '),
(5178,E'430 3rd Ave NE',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56304,NULL,NULL,E'Jefferson School (add\'n)',E'Pinault-Truszinski & Co.',E'1967',E'Addition and remodel ($291,803 budget); Builder: D.M. Noyes Const. Co. (Minneapolis); part of what was the largest school bond issue in Central Minnesota when passed ($7,875,000); Closed in 2004, bought and turned into a parochial school.'),
(5179,E'5800 Ridgewood Rd',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Westwood Elementary School',E'Jackson-Hahn Assoc.',E'1969-70',E'Announced and designed in 1968 as part of what was the largest school bond issue in Central Minnesota when passed ($7,875,000); this was one of the final projects of the Jackson-Hahn partnership as Hahn jumped to Traynor & Hermanson in 1969, which was renamed Traynor, Hermanson & Hawn in May 1969.'),
(5180,E'1115 4th Ave N',E'Sauk Rapids',E'MN',56379,NULL,NULL,E'Good Shepherd Lutheran Home',E'Buetow & Assocs',E'1962-63',E'The original phase (planned since 1960) was funded by 17 central Minnesotan congregations of the Missouri Synod, the $650,000 structure was designed to house 100 beds arranged in four wings with the center of the building (concave curves between each wing) used for joint activity rooms, and 3 outdoor patio; those patios have been mostly eliminated by the many additions.'),
(5181,E'1120 15th Ave S',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'South Junior High School',E'Traynor & Hermanson and Virgil E. Siddens',E'1960-61',E'Originally planned for September 1960, but "planning problems" by the architects pushed things to 1961, which in turn was put into concern by a steel strike. The two story front portion of the building (west-facing) was designed to contain the classrooms and the rear was for shops and physical education quarters; all articles reference the pairing of the two architectural firms; as of July 2019 the structure\'s exterior looks close to the original \'60 sketch.'),
(5182,E'717 W St Germain St',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'Zapp National Bank',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1961-62',E'The two-story structure was mostly new construction, with the easternmost section being the original Zapp Bank building; the new building is mostly glass and features granite on the base; interior design by A. Mooreman & Co.; Builder: Wahl Const. Co.; while no longer a bank, by July 2019 the exterior remains in great shape; a large, decorative granite plaque sits on the western facade: when the first artist the architects tried to hire was busy, the artist recommended his student do the drawing; the student ended up being Edward Zapp III (son of the bank president)... it looks like something a student would draw.'),
(5183,E'1644 St Croix Circle',E'Golden Valley',E'MN',55422,NULL,NULL,E'Jake and Marjorie Barnett Residence',E'Jake Barnett, Builder',E'1966',E'Jacob (Jake) J. Barnett ran Barnett Builders for 40yrs; House was featured in its own Minneapolis Tribune article (May 26, 1968); two years of planning to create an house with angles and curves to take advantage of views in all directions; owners focused on adding soundproofing both from the outside and within the house; the downstairs rec-room was interesting, with walls "covered with carpeting (\'practically indestructible\') in vertical stripes of blues, green, black and gray. The same colors are used on the floor, only in squares. Even the light above the pool table has its shade carpeted" and it also had a shuffle-board court; the couple used the same color scheme throughout the house; curved staircase; the foyer floor was Mexican onyx stone (with matching table); some of the living room wall was black marble (with matching table); exterior was rough-sawn vertical redwood siding and charcoal brick; with hand-split shakes on the cornice of the almost mansard roof.'),
(5184,E'13 24th Ave N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Sporleder\'s Heating, Plumbing and Sheet Metal',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1961',E'Simple 42x76-foot, one-story cement block store building with a geometric pattern on the sides; the $27,000 structure was build by Richard Sporleder and had a basement. '),
(5185,E'548 17th St N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Andrew & Carol Hilger Residence',E'Unknown',E'1960',E'Poured concrete construction facing the Mississippi with a master bedroom offering panoramic views; the street facade has Moderne elements; Andy Hilger (1930-2013) started in radio and eventually purchased a share of WJON which he turned into a major cable provider for the St. Cloud region before selling it and going back owning radio stations; in the late 1980s he was named one of St. Cloud\'s most influential citizens (they sold the house in 1988).'),
(5186,E'1700 Hillcrest Rd',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'John & Irene Wahl Residence',E'Unknown',E'c.1960',E'John A. Wahl (1930-2015) was a scion of one of the major builders in the St. Cloud area, taking over in the 1960s, he also served on local gov\'t; Irene M. Wahl (1931-2015) helped run the family company and made their house\'s garden well-regarded (was a regular winner in best holiday lights in a local competition in the mid-1960s); married for 62 years, they died within 14 hours of each other.'),
(5187,E'2719 3rd St N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Redeemer Lutheran Church',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1962-63',E'Bold, concrete roof "made of \'half umbrellas\' supported” by tapered concrete columns (the walls between are brick) with a sculptural concrete bell tower; interior "features lightweight concrete block walls and a ceiling of natural finish concrete" with brick floors. The $265,000 structure was designed to seat 555. Construction began on April 17, 1962. There has been a single-story addition on the west side of the building that obscures the design, but the east facade is still in its original form.'),
(5188,E'615 1st St N',E'Cold Spring',E'MN',56320,NULL,NULL,E'Assumption Nursing Home',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1962-63',E'The original section of the 10-acre property features a 219x209-foot structure built around a central courtyard (still extant as of 2019); the exterior is split-face granite; Builder: Gohman Const. Co. (St. Joseph); many subsequent additions.'),
(5189,E'5 McLeland Rd',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56393,NULL,NULL,E'Fingerhut Manufacturing Plant',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1961-62',E'The 100,000sf building was built in a hurry using and used the area\'s first hyperbolic paraboloid roof (using a thin shell of concrete) to allow maximum "spacing between columns supporting the roof, with a series of square bays centered on each concrete column. Purpose is to get a fireproof building at less cost than steel and concrete." The exterior wall looks like a typical square plant, but the aerial view reveals the roof design.'),
(5190,E'3139 Blackheath Dr',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'Jerry & Ann P. Helgeson Residence',E'Humleker, Richard D.',E'1966',E'Luxury rambler with low-pitched roof, large living room windows taking advantage of a gable; tennis court; featured on a 1974 AAUW home tour; home was designed to blend into a hill and use natural materials: blending Minnesota limestone, flagstone, various woods, marble, "and unusual indoor plantings." Jerry Helgeson (d.2014) was a partner at Gold\'n Plump (now GNP).'),
(5191,E'3143 Blackheath Dr',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'John W. & Patricia Sathe Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Triangular-shaped footprint allowing for three gables to form a folded, accordion pattern; very open and airy on the inside; John W. Sathe (1916-70) owned the St. Cloud Launderette.'),
(5192,E'3144 Blackheath Dr',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'Teigen Residence',E'Unknown ',E'c.1960',E'Luxury, flat-roof rambler on a golf course; vertical wood siding, stonework accent wall, horizontal fascia on the roof edge.'),
(5193,E'1606 Cooper Ave S',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'Byron E. Thoele Residence',E'Unknown',E'1963',E'Flat-roof, modernist house; President of Thoele Dental Laboratory; sons constantly cited for speeding in the 1960s (when they would list your home address in the newspaper); the Thoeles moved to Texas in the 1970s due to Byron\'s health. '),
(5194,E'2019 Hillcrest Dr',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Arthur L. & Romana S. Wahl Residence',E'House Beautiful plan',E'1965-66',E'After retiring from the family\'s construction company, Wahl had this rambler built using a plan in "House Beautiful" magazine by Home Planners, Inc., family room paneled in pecan; featured on 1968 AAUW home tour.'),
(5195,E'25926 Lake Rd',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'Al & Marlene Burger Residence',E'Unknown',E'1968',E'One-story rambler built close to Pleasant Lake, taking full advantage of views; the exterior is granite with a "white marble roof" and double-door front entry in lacquered red; the interior features walnut paneling, woodwork, and beamed ceiling; California driftstone was hand-laid for a feature wall in the living room as well as the fireplace wall in the family room; featured on 1968 AAUW home tour; the Burgers coincidentally ran numerous restaurants and clubs over the years, including the extant 400 Club on Pleasant Lake (next to the house).'),
(5196,E'4130 Lexington Ave N',E'Shoreview',E'MN',55126,NULL,NULL,E'Nob Hill apartments',E'Budinger, Jean-Paul',E'1969-70',E'Developed by Bel-Mar Builders (Budinger was their staff architect); Massive, horseshoe-shaped apartment complex: The design is two apartment buildings arranged with a recreation building at the base of the horseshoe; shake mansard roof over a brick exterior with two-story arches over the windows; Later renamed Shoreview Hills Apartments.'),
(5197,E'4650 65th St SE',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56304,NULL,NULL,E'Fredric Wemlinger Residence',E'Wemlinger, Fredric',E'1969',E'Architect\'s own house; Fredric Wemlinger moved to the area from Chicago and designed this house based on his conception of Minnesota living: near water with plenty of trees around; the 4 bedroom house was sited on a hill overlooking Round Lake and oriented to give all rooms a lake view from sliding glass doors open to separate balconies; exterior is vertical cedar boards; interior\'s major focal point is a three-story fireplace core that is visible from all the major living areas; featured on 1970 and 1974 AAUW home tour.'),
(5198,E'216 8th Ave',E'Waite Park',E'MN',56387,NULL,NULL,E'McKinley School',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1964-65',E'Otherwise typical brick and steel school building accented with walls curving outward for main entrance on 8th Avenue; Builder: Antler Corp. (St Paul); eventually closed and converted into the McKinley Area Learning Center.'),
(5199,E'1212 29th Ave N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'North Junior High School',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1964-65',E'Originally a pair of rectangular forms laid out in a vaguely T-shape; Builder: Sheehy Const. (Minneapolis). '),
(5200,E'915 2nd St N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'U. S. Post Office II',E'Unknown',E'1964-65',E'Granite-trimmed structure initially built with separate 8-stall garage; Builder: Jerome Building Co. (Detroit, MI).'),
(5201,E'124 1st Ave SE',E'St Joseph',E'MN',56374,NULL,NULL,E'John F. Kennedy Elementary School',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1967-68',E'The building was designed to have six of the classrooms in the nonagonal "Pod" which consisted of a polygonal core with six classrooms arrayed around with with folding partitions between them to allow for team teaching; a rectangular gym/multipurpose portion is attached by a wing consisting of offices and other support facilities; After the campus moved to a new Kennedy school campus just SE of the town, the structure was leased to Little Saints Academy, a private child care facility'),
(5202,E'301 Montrose Rd',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'St. Cloud Country Club clubhouse',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1968-69',E'The two-level structure with a fascinating roof design has 6420sf on the upper level and 7750sf on the lower level; Consulting Engineers: Gausmen & Moore (St Paul); Builder: D.M. Noyes Const. Co.'),
(5203,E'100 W Pleasure Dr',E'Litchfield',E'MN',55355,NULL,NULL,E'Lake Ripley Elementary School',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1968-69',E'Originally a 26-classroom, open school model capable of housing 900 students; the $1.15M structure was built on a 14-acre parcel;  former director Sharon Roberston (who worked there for 44 of the first 50 years), said "The school used to use accordion walls to separate classrooms. The separators became difficult to use" and space issues led to more areas being converted to classrooms.'),
(5204,E'2101 15th Ave NW ',E'Willmar',E'MN',56201,NULL,NULL,E'Willmar Junior College',E'Traynor, Hermanson & Hahn',E'1969-70',E'Phases I and II of the junior college; it was merged with Hutchinson\'s junior college for a 2-campus Ridgewater College.'),
(5205,E'900 5th St',E'Holdingford',E'MN',56340,NULL,NULL,E'Holdingford High School',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1969-70',E'Several additions; one of the final projects before the firm became Traynor, Hermanson & Hahn (announced days after the sketches were published).'),
(5206,E'1445 MN-23 Trunk',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56304,NULL,NULL,E'St. Cloud Elks Lodge No. 516',E'Traynor & Hermanson',E'1969-70',E'Classic mansard shingle bunker; Builder: W. Gohman Const. (St. Joseph); one of the final projects before the firm became Traynor, Hermanson & Hahn; the club moved out in 1984; the building is apparently now offices for a local company that owns surrounding warehouses; the lot was originally sources “at cost” from a local industrial company.'),
(5207,E'442 2nd St SE',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56304,NULL,NULL,E'St Augustine Church',E'Freerks, Sperl & Flynn',E'1960-61',E'The first new Catholic church in the city in 30 years; the $315,000 church uses granite on both the interior and exteriors, Terrazzo flooring, ceilings using laminated wood, seating room for 50; 112ft brick bell tower (90ft brick tower, topped with a 14ft cross) has 3 exposed bells named John, Benedict and Scholastic. The program called for creating a "simple, dignified structure, using natural materials – wood, granite, and glass; a shelter that houses a special function, and a parish church where man can feel in close communion with God." The interior design features a raised side area to hold the secondary choir, Way of the Cross, mothers\' room, and sacristies. The sacristies are organized to provide correlation between sanctuary, sacristy, and parish house. The baptistry is at the entrance and sheltered by a glass screen from the narthex. Builder: Cy Kufflel.'),
(5208,E'110 Minnesota Ave',E'Tintah',E'MN',56583,NULL,NULL,E'St Gall\'s Catholic Church',E'Dreher Freerks Sperl Flynn',E'1962-63',E'Fairly large church & rectory in a fairly small town; similar in overall form to the St. Augustine Church the firm designed in St. Cloud. The $156,000 complex connected the rectory to the church via the rectory vestibule and church sacristy. The sanctuary was designed to seat 300. A free-standing steel and brick tower with cross stands 67ft, the tower is striking for how it appears to rest on 3 delicate (but steel) feet. The main church uses brick interior and exterior, laminated wood arches and wood deck for the interior ceiling; the baptistry was placed in the narthex of the church. Builder: Eian & Ness (Fergus Falls). The structure replaced an older church (1896) and rectory (1904) that were to the south. As the church had an existing parish hall (1952), the church was built without a basement. '),
(5209,E'534 5th St N',E'Cold Spring',E'MN',56320,NULL,NULL,E'Rocori High School',E'Horan-Hustad Architects',E'1968-69',E'The curious name is actually an acronym (ROCORI) for the 3 towns it serves: Rockville, Cold Spring, and Richmond.'),
(5210,E'2301 8th Ave NW',E'Austin',E'MN',55912,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1960',E'Another example of Austin\'s mid-century houses, well-sited on a slope with vertical redwood siding on upper level with horizontal fascias on the flat roof and extensive wrap-around deck; Kasota stone lover level, also used inside (including on an incredible fireplace wall with a large circular opening); tasteful wood paneling; some clerestory windows; mid-century wrought-iron stair rail; exposed post-and-beam in living room; in very good shape as of 2020 real estate listing.'),
(5211,E'4101 W Division St',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'Crossroads Center',E'Mastny, George G.',E'1964-66',E'Opening anchor tenant were Sears, Roebuck & Co. and J.C. Penney\'s Co., with other nat\'l tenants including Woolworth\'s, Walgreen Drugs, National Tea, and Kinney Shoes; it featured a 35,000sf center court with trees, flowers, conversation areas, rest benches, and greenery ("air-conditioned or heated to 72-degrees throughout the year"); at the time the nearly 400,000sf of shopping space made it the third-largest mall in Minnesota after Southdale (Edina) and Apache Plaza (St. Anthony); developed by the Crossroads Center Corp.; Builder: Ernest M. Ganley; expanded in 1995, renovated in 2004.'),
(5212,E'2400 Sherwood Hills Rd',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55305,NULL,NULL,E'Ronald & Marjorie Vegemast Residence',E'Mastny, George G.',E'1960',E'Located on a 3.54 acre lot wooded lot on the high ridge of Sherwood Hills, among the classic mid-century homes of the Sherwood area; Mastny listed it as a primary example of his work in the 1962 AIA directory; Ronald G. Vegemast was an electrical engineer who went on to start his own consulting firm in \'84 and develop emergency calling services around the world; former president of the MN Society of Professional Engineers; Ron passed in 2016, house was still in the family by 2020.'),
(5213,E'5 Brown Rd S',E'Orono',E'MN',55356,NULL,NULL,E'George G. Mastney Residence',E'Mastny, George G.',E'1963',E'Architect\'s own house; Featured in a 1964 Minneapolis Tribune article: Mastny emphasized that “Flexibility is the essence of design. If you can get 10 feet to do what 12 feet might do, you have saved 15 dollars a square foot. Planning is essential. To get multiple uses and economy of space, contemporary design does this better than conventional design.” The piece noted the "young Wayzata architect" and his wife “cut costs by doing their own contracting and finishing much of the interior themselves.” The 24x50ft footprint features an upper floor focused on for family living, with a screened-in deck measuring 10x50ft; the lower floor includes a rec area, 3 bedrooms, and an exit to a paved terrace; The main floor is designed so that "nearly all the walls are doors. Glass doors lead to the redwood deck on one side. Birch slab doors slide out of the walls to close off a bedroom-den area at one end of the house and a dining room at the other end of the house” and has a vaulted ceiling; exterior is concrete block and redwood siding; roof over the vaulted ceiling is copper-clad heavy paper that was originally designed as flashing material but cost a quarter as much as a typical copper roof of the time.'),
(5214,E'2100 Northdale Blvd NW',E'Coon Rapids',E'MN',55433,NULL,NULL,E'Village Ten Shopping Center',E'Mastny Assoc.',E'1969-70',E'Developed on 23-acres, the $5M shopping center originally included a Shopper\'s City discount store, 1,000-seat theater, large recreation area, and an apartment complex; Builder: Erickson Development Co.'),
(5215,E'24560 Co Rd 7',E'St Augusta',E'MN',56301,NULL,NULL,E'St. Mary Help of Christians School',E'Pinault-Truszinski & Co.',E'1964-65',E'Replaced a 4-room structure built in 1892; the new structure designed to feature 8 classrooms (nylon-carpeted, which the pastor said "is noted to be especially quiet and asy to clean."), a multi-purpose room (gym/cafeteria/parish center), plus the typical school support rooms; Builder: Willard Gohman Const. (St Joseph).'),
(5216,E'2300 Old Shakopee Rd W',E'Bloomington',E'MN',55431,NULL,NULL,E'Werness Brothers Funeral Chapel ',E'Raugland, Entrikin, Domholt & King',E'1969-71',E'Large, sprawling funeral chapel built next to what was originally Bloomington city hall; this was Werness Brother\'s 3rd chapel; the company was bought by rival Washburn-McReavy (c. 1981); design process began in 1966, per files at Northwest Architectural Archives. Landscape designed by Dundee Landscaping.'),
(5217,E'3400 98th St W',E'Bloomington',E'MN',55431,NULL,NULL,E'Bloomington Community Ice Garden',E'Stahl-Wolf-Peterson',E'1969-70',E'The original name was supposed to be "Ice Center," but a threat of legal challenge from the owners of Golden Valley\'s “Ice Center Skating Ring” (5800 Wayzata Blvd in Golden Valley, later renamed Breck Arena and demolished by 1999) led to the name Bloomington Community Ice Garden, then shortened to simply the Bloomington Ice Garden and nicknamed “BIG” after its acronym; Rink 2 added in 1975, Rink 3 (seating for 2400) in 1993; Rink 1 renovated in 2007. '),
(5218,E'14091 Stonegate Lane',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55345,NULL,NULL,E'Logan W. Johnson Residence',E'Logan W. Johnson, Designer',E'1966',E'Johnson was a designer, and partner in Polivka Logan Designs. Stonegate was developed in the mid \'60s by E. Harold Johnson, consisting of mostly deluxe ranch styles (with a lot of contemporary styling) built from the mid \'60s through the early \'70s on a custom-basis (his work here and on adjacent Forrest Hill were the highest elevations in Hennepin County). The owner, Logan Johnson, was also the designer and he (and his wife) loved color!  I would love to see all those color photos.  It had purple carpeting!  And, as the owner noted, "If you\'re going to use purple, it has to be just the right purple," Johnson emphasized. "We went through 15 dye lots to get just the color we wanted." The carpeting also served as a baseboard, running up the wall for a few inches. He used wide overhang of eaves to prevent glare; he added a pass-through between the kitchen and garage for moving groceries. Garnered a Western Wood Products Association award in 1967 for effective use of wood.'),
(5219,E'1007 14th St E',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55404,NULL,NULL,E'Augustana Home Infirmary Building',E'Patch & Erickson',E'1960-61',E'The $900,000 nursing home addition to accommodate 102 individuals greatly expanded the Augustana Home, and included a library, lounge, activity areas, and coffee shop; the same project enlarged and modernized the dining room, kitchen, and heating plant of the old buildings (which are mostly no longer extant); Builder: George Madsen Const. Co. This building came at a pivotal moment for the organization, which was founded in 1896 as a "mission colony" to care for aged & infirm, children, and young women: until 1960 it was maintained by a single congregation (First Augustana Lutheran), but then expanded to include Cavalry, Diamond Lake, Emanuel, Gustavus Adolphus, Hope, and Messiah Lutheran churches. Originally four-story, but designed for the addition of up to 2 more (1 was later added). A second wing, forming a L-shape with the original, was built from 1964-65 for $597,640 (also designed by Patch & Erickson; Builder: Adolfson & Peterson) and boosted the capacity for the facility to 285 residents.'),
(5220,E'4646 Humboldt Ave N',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55412,NULL,NULL,E'Fire Station No. 20',E'Patch & Erickson',E'1962',NULL),
(5221,E'115 S Fremont St',E'Lewiston',E'MN',55952,NULL,NULL,E'Lewiston Elementary School',E'Patch & Erickson',E'c.1960s',NULL),
