(5277,E'1550 Pennsylvania Ave N',E'Golden Valley',E'MN',55427,NULL,NULL,E'Parade Home No. 24 (1967)',E'Unknown',E'1967',E'Builder: Nick M. Loscheider Const. Co.; Described in the Parade listing as "An L-shaped tri-level California Contemporary on beautiful wooded lot. A Medallion home of rugged rough sawn cedar with 4 bedrooms, 2 1/2 baths, foyer, formal dining room, \'Quiet Room\' family room with beamed ceiling. Kitchen with dining area and built-in appliances. Intercom System. Central air conditioning." featured by Northwestern Bell as being "equipped with the newest in telephone conveniences"; the Minneapolis Home Builders Association gave the house 2nd place in its 1967 "Reggie" awards category for $30,000-$40,000 homes; later owned by an architect who made improvements. '),
(5278,E'1345 Fairlawn Way',E'Golden Valley',E'MN',55416,NULL,NULL,E'Irving Brooks Residence',E'Baker, Edward F.',E'1964',E'The design process between architect and client included having the 4 Brooks children "show us on the blueprint everywhere they would be. From this we figured out where the most traffic would be and used slate instead of carpet in those areas." Dining room was separated from the kitchen by a counter with louvered shutters that could slide across completely to shut off the kitchen from the dining room when entertaining guest; front entry had open beams surrounding a mature oak to give a tree-house effect. There was originally an outdoor pool. Brooks was head of Twin City produce companies H. Brooks & Co.'),
(5279,E'1400 W 94th St',E'Bloomington',E'MN',55431,NULL,NULL,E'Donaldson Co. Headquarters and Research Facility',E'Hammel & Green',E'1961-62',E'The original, $750,000 facility consisted of 3 buildings: a 27,200sqft office building, a 21,200sqft research center, and a small utility and garage building (the two larger buildings connected by an 86ft corridor)'),
