(5316,E'6920 Wayzata Blvd',E'Golden Valley',E'MN',55426,NULL,NULL,E'Uncle John Pancake House',E'Unknown',E'1962-63',E'Uncle John\'s may have been the local franchisee of what became Perkins (Matt and Ivan Perkins opened what was called Smithies Pancake House in Cincinnati in 1957; MN was one of the most aggressive franchises); by 2020 it was still used as a Perkins Restaurant, but the façade is a generic Perkins; major alterations in 2002 broke up the simple, single gable roof; MNHS has 1963 photo of its original appearance (NP 286472).'),
(5317,E'14620 Woodhill Circle',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55345,NULL,NULL,E'Edward J Halcin Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Two-story with basement; lots of floor-to-ceiling windows across the southern façade for passive solar gain, with far fewer on the north (mostly clerestory ribbons for upper floor bathrooms); functional but tastefully proportioned. The entry area has a mosaic floor in a starburst pattern. Brick fireplace (painted white) with stone hearth. Kitchen passthrough to the dining room. The upper kitchen cabinets are hung to float, mosaic tile floor. Breakfast nook off of it at one of the corners with windows on both sides (the other front corner is the living room). Has an unfinished basement. Owner was a Honeywell engineer, after an initial stop at McDonnell Douglas in California; Still in the Edward J Halcin Trust as of 2020; Halchin died in January, age 98. Lot appears to have been much larger, with remnant lot lines that appear to indicate it originally had a driveway to Williston in the west. Went up for sale for the first time in May 2022, overall in reasonable shape. '),
