(5323,E'700 Buffalo St',E'Mondovi',E'WI',54755,NULL,NULL,E'Buffalo Memorial Hospital',E'Magney, John R.',E'1962-63',E'48-bed hospital; this particular piece of land was selected over one west of town because of its prominence from Highway 10, as well as views of the surrounding hills and Beef River; plans made in 1961-62.'),
(5324,E'900 4th St N',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55401,NULL,NULL,E'Salvation Army Men\'s Social Service Center (add\'n)',E'Magney, John R.',E'1963-64',E'After the old Salvation Army HQ was condemned to make room for the interstate, they bought the former Pratt\'s Express Co. and Gold Bond Co. buildings; then planned a major $1.05M addition and renovation; the 3-story addition on the north side of the complex, accommodating 250 men.'),
(5325,E'7585 Viron Rd NE',E'Fridley',E'MN',55432,NULL,NULL,E'Viron Industries, Inc.',E'Magney, John R.',E'1965',E'Aerospace manufacturing facility: $500,000, 40,000 sq ft metal building for producing inflatable plastic space vehicles;; Address alternately written as "7585 Hwy 65 NE" as Viron is a frontage road.'),
(5326,E'600 Rice St E',E'Wayzata',E'MN',55391,NULL,NULL,E'Wayzata Fire Station',E'Magney, John R.',E'1965-66',NULL),
(5327,E'1200 Oakdale Ave',E'West St Paul',E'MN',55118,NULL,NULL,E'Archbishop Brady High School',E'Unknown',E'1963-64',E'The first co-institutional (co-ed) high school in the St. Paul Archdiocese, the $2M campus was designed to keep boys and girls classes separate "as much as possible"; Named in honor of the aggressive school building push by Archbishop William O. Brady; Builder: Carl Bolander & Sons Co.; school closed due to financial difficulties in 1991; campus purchased as new home for the St. Croix Lutheran High School in 1992, spending about $5M in total ($2.23M for purchase, rest for renovation).'),
(5328,E'1643 Virginia Ave S',E'St Louis Park',E'MN',55426,NULL,NULL,E'Robert D. Hanson Residence',E'Hanson, Robert D.',E'1962',E'Architect\'s own house;  was a longtime partner at Patch & Erickson (for a time known as Patch, Erickson, Madson & Hanson) before working with Matrix Architects; died of lung cancer in 1987, age 62; estate sold house in 1989. Split-level with large overhanging eaves and lots of windows front and back.'),
(5329,E'14770 Canada Ave W',E'Rosemount',E'MN',55068,NULL,NULL,E'Rosemount Methodist Church',E'Hills, Gilbertson & Hayes ',E'1962-63',NULL),
(5330,E'3366 Oakdale Ave N',E'Robbinsdale',E'MN',55422,NULL,NULL,E'Oakdale Medical Center',E'Liebenberg, Kaplan & Glotter',E'1964-65',E'The 6-story, $1.2M building with facade of brick and acredite, connected by tunnel to North Memorial Hospital to the south; developed by Oakdale, Inc. (headed by Herbert Elsen); Builder: D.J. Kranz, Co.; upper floor sees some significant changes from original sketch (the builders needed permit for any building 6-floors or taller); major subsequent additions: 1971-72 adjacent parking structure as well as 1986 office addition to SE; purchased by North Memorial Clinic; as of 2020 named the Robbinsdale Medical Building.'),
(5331,E'9350 Blaylock Circle',E'Credit River Township',E'MN',55372,NULL,NULL,E'Walter M. Schmidt House',E'Howe, John H. ',E'1967-69',E'Addition, 1981-82; over the years it has become the only remaining house on the street and surrounded almost entirely by the Murphy-Hanrehan Park Reserve; as of December 2020 it is still owned by Schmidt. Scott County\'s assessor has good photos of the home, which features a bridge leading to the front door, thing wood beams all around. Has several matching out buildings.'),
(5332,E'5825 St Croix Ave N',E'Golden Valley',E'MN',55422,NULL,NULL,E'Colonial Acres Rest Home',E'Fasth, Hillstrom & Horty',E'1961',E'Original wing was a 40-bed, $300,000 nursing home; it has since had several expansions on the north and south sides of the original wing.'),
(5333,E'4531 36 1/2 St W',E'St Louis Park',E'MN',55416,NULL,NULL,E'Chateau Monterey Apartments',E'Stageberg, James',E'1960-61',E'Inexplicable name for modern design; the 5-building development included 54-units, cost $600,000, and had a swimming pool until 2015; part of a larger 100-unit development, along with previously built Monterey Villa and Monterey West; all developed by owner/builder Richard Neslund Const. Co.'),
(5334,E'4545 36 1/2 St W',E'St Louis Park',E'MN',55416,NULL,NULL,E'Chateau Monterey II',E'Stageberg, James',E'1961-62',E'20-units (1 & 2 bedroom) extending the design of Chateau Monterey and the silly naming scheme started with Monterey Villa and Monterey West.'),
(5335,E'88 E Pleasant Lake Rd',E'North Oaks',E'MN',55127,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1969',E'The walk-out is curved to take full advantage of peninsular lot; brick entryway and lower-level living room (open to top) with floating stair; wood-paneled interior elsewhere; lots of windows taking advantage of view;'),
(5336,E'14805 Excelsior Blvd',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55345,NULL,NULL,E'Glen Lake Animal Hospital',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Veterinary clinic originally owned by Dr. Robert M. Dingel, who made news in 1965 when he pleaded guilty to "burglarizing numerous suburban homes just for self-satisfaction" with loot found at his medical office; he continued practicing there until he sold the practice in 1982.'),
(5337,E'5121 Woodgate Ct',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55345,NULL,NULL,E'Don & Carol Haugness House',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Vertical wood siding on front-walk-out concrete block base; exterior in good shape as of 2019 sale; interior modernized significantly; built as part of "Thorson\'s Woodgate Addition," consisting of 60 wooded lots. Builder: Hugh B. Thorson'),
(5338,E'6400 Stauder Circle',E'Edina',E'MN',55436,NULL,NULL,E'H. David Dalquist Residence',E'Unknown',E'1965',E'House with Wrightian elements, apparently large addition to back; blue stone exterior with shingle fascia on the low-pitched roof; Dalquist was founder and Chairman of Nordic Ware (Northland Aluminum Products, Inc.); The house was cited in 1967 for having a "large contemporary kitchen planned for a combination kitchen and family room overlooking an indoor swimming pool."'),
(5339,E'13001 Melody Lane',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55305,NULL,NULL,E'John Korngiebel Residence',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Architect\'s own house; exterior is a fairly standard split-level around a center entrance; interior photos from 2018 sale show some thought was put into interior design, so it is plausible Korngiebel did some design to it.'),
(5340,E'4227 Queens Way',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55345,NULL,NULL,E'Gorden M. Lee Residence',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Sprawling walk-out rambler; cedar siding and vaulted ceilings; Part of builder/developer Robert Mason\'s Royal Hills development in Minnetonka; Mason (who was in his 20s when it began) built many different styles of homes in the development: ramblers, split levels, two story colonials and a few contemporaries. Price range was in the mid-$20ks to mid-$30ks. Mason was in his mid 20s when he started building homes in the development.'),
(5341,E'6 Badger Lane',E'North Oaks',E'MN',55127,NULL,NULL,E'Thomas S. Hay Residence',E'Unknown',E'1968',E'Reserved, walk-out rambler; beamed ceiling; stone fireplace and brick fireplace; site is in between two fairways with houses on either side (could\'ve taken better advantage…); Builder: Rebers Const. Co. (Sidney B. Rebers)'),
(5342,E'1235 Bolley Dr',E'Fargo',E'ND',58102,NULL,NULL,E'Heating Plant (add\'n) (NDSU)',E'Johnson & Lightowler',E'1962',E'Addition to SE corner of 1903-04 heating plant structure: removing coal bunkers, providing room for a new 1,402 HP boiler, and moving/upgrading the rail car unloading system; Builder: Stoutland Const. Co.; a 1972 addition to the north side of the existing plant to house a then-experimental gas boiler.'),
(5343,E'1333 12th Ave N',E'Fargo',E'ND',58102,NULL,NULL,E'Burgum Hall (NDSU)',E'Johnson & Lightowler',E'1962',E'First place in the 1964 design contest by the AIA chapter of North Dakota; the 3-story women\'s dormitory was designed to house 180 students; features barrel vault over common area on main level. Originally, residents faced strict rules as one mandated that all drapes be drawn by 7:00 pm; named Jessamine Slaughter Burgum Hall in honor of the first female student at NDSU (then NDAC), the 2nd building at the school to be named after her (the first used her maiden name, which Trustees feared that students would refer to the building as "Slaughter House" rather than "Slaughter Hall") '),
(5344,E'2607 Birchmont Dr NE',E'Bemidji',E'MN',56601,NULL,NULL,E'Carl Berggren Residence',E'Unknown',E'1964',E'Modest, flat-roof modern rambler with big windows facing towards street and Lake Bemidji beyond; horizontal wood siding; detatched garage.'),
(5345,E'2722 Birchmont Dr NE',E'Bemidji',E'MN',56601,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. E.K. Hauffer Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Modern house fronting Lake Bemidji; rambler with horizontal redwood siding with clerestory windows and contrasting brick wall facing street; very low-pitch, gravel roof with thin fascia.'),
(5346,E'310 Birchwood Dr',E'Stillwater',E'MN',55082,NULL,NULL,E'Curt & MaryJo Jackson Residence',E'Klundt, Knudson & Assoc.',E'1963',E'Madison-based architectural firm, Specific architect was Jack Klundt; second owner (bought the house in 1970), Curt & MaryJoi Jackson, had Klundt to involved in updates in the 1980s and a roof replacement in the 2000s (Klundt passed away in 2020, age 99), updates kept the mid-century style; 3br, 2 bath and a finished basement; carport in front of the house — the Jackson’s loved it because unloading groceries from the trunk was only 12 steps to the kitchen counter. The landscape was finished in recent years by landscape architect Jim Hagstrom of Savannah Designs in Afton.'),
(5347,E'426 Lake St',E'Excelsior',E'MN',55331,NULL,NULL,E'Hour Glass Cleaners',E'Unknown',E'1965',E'Delightful dry cleaners with ribbon roof out front; Owners: B.C. Burdick & Howard Anderson; plans approved in 1964.'),
(5348,E'1420 NW 4th St',E'Grand Rapids',E'MN',55744,NULL,NULL,E'Pine Grove Motel',E'Unknown',E'c.1960s',E'Typical, single-story roadside motel featuring a classic mid-century sign.'),
(5349,E'11 Runestone Dr',E'Kensington',E'MN',56343,NULL,NULL,E'Our Lady of the Runestone Church',E'Unknown',E'1964',E'Church named after the Kensington Runestone, a noted 19th-century hoax by local farmer, Swedish immigrant Olof Öhman, who claimed he unearthed a 14th-century runestone showing Viking exploration of the area; the decision to name the church after then-widely discredited hoax came from a belief that it was somehow real and that the few Latin letters on it (AVM) had to mean Ave Maria Virgo; Asymmetrical roof design on sanctuary, appearing to favor southern sun for heating; unclear what portions may have been additions.'),
(5350,E'114 Sandy Hook Rd',E'Chanhassen',E'MN',55317,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Bloomberg, Herbert',E'1963',E'Over-the-top design by Bloomberg’s team that appears to have had some equally over-the-top attempts at interior remodeling; still, many of Bloomberg’s favorite design elements in his "Rustic Modern" style remain, including an indoor pool; flagstone floors, vaulted ceilings with large wood beams, big fireplace walls, and a resistance to square/rectangle shaped rooms; on Lotus Lake, not far from Bloomberg’s own house.'),
(5351,E'19 Main St N',E'St Michael',E'MN',55376,NULL,NULL,E'St. Michael Catholic School (add\'n)',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Substantial, 3-level addition to existing 1940 subtly Moderne school building'),
(5352,E'129 Outer Dr',E'Silver Bay',E'MN',55614,NULL,NULL,E'Silver Bay Arena',E'Unknown',E'1966',E'Renamed the Frank Rukavina Arena in 1976; same layout as Lake County Arena (also built in 1966 with same blueprints and builder).'),
(5353,E'301 8th Ave',E'Two Harbors',E'MN',55616,NULL,NULL,E'Lake County Arena',E'Unknown',E'1966',E'Same layout as Silver Bay Arena (also built in 1966 with same blueprints and builder).'),
(5354,E'8084 South Minnesuing Acres Dr',E'Lake Nebagamon',E'WI',54849,NULL,NULL,E'Minnesuing Acres',E'Bloomberg, Herbert',E'1961',E'Originally a family retreat build by Gold Bond Stamps/Carlson Companies founder Curtis L. Carlson, it was also called Gold Bond Lodge; the family later converted it (with some additions) to a corporate retreat facility—fitting as much of their business was in hospitality. Carlson built it as a surprise for his family: the family already had a modest cabin on a small island on Lake Minnesuing, he built it on a shore hidden from view from their side of the island. The original home has many of the features associated with Herb Bloomberg’s "Rustic Modern" style vision of luxury, including vaulted ceilings with large wood beams, indoor pool, flagstone floors, big fireplace walls, resistance to square/rectangle shaped rooms, etc. '),
