(5375,E'602 12th Ave E',E'Alexandria',E'MN',56308,NULL,NULL,E'Emmanuel Episcopal Church',E'Unknown',E'1965-66',E'Built to replace the previous church that was razed in \'65; A-frame with traditional styling.'),
(5376,E'1144 29th Ave N',E'St Cloud',E'MN',56303,NULL,NULL,E'Atonement Lutheran Church',E'Unknown',E'1961-62',E'Congregation founded in 1961; first phase of building (1961-62) consisted of a 33\'x120\' one-story, flat roof structure with a 33\'x65\' main church out of brick and block (cost: $50,353), it currently sits on the northwest corner of the site; phase 2 in 1968, the 3rd phase added the current sanctuary in 1978-79, designed to seat 400 ($470,000), with a 4th phase in 1992 adding new space for education, fellowship, and offices; the 1979 sanctuary was designed to make an architectural statement in the northside neighborhood (to compete and “counteract” the North Junior High School across the street) and communicate "friendliness and openness to worshippers inside and people outside," the semi-circular shape was designed as "sort of like a theater in the half round" making the chancel area fairly close to all worshippers, with the entrance being from near the front rather than the back.'),
(5377,E'337 Mesabi Dr',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Split-level with siting that is askew from others on the block (appears to give upper level living room a better view) façade uses a large amount of field stone; garage added in \'67 (may have originally been a car port).'),
(5378,E'2900 Beltline Hwy E',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'Hibbing Area Vocational-Technical Institute',E'Unknown',E'1965',E'Also shortened to Hibbing AVTI; eventually sold in 2011 and converted into an office-manufacturing complex. Interesting curved wall element adding windows to interior.'),
(5379,E'211 Highland Dr',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1964',E'Split-level, bent floorplan with tuck-under garage; brick lower level with vertical wood siding on upper; low-pitched roof with beams extending to overhang; the outer portion of the bend forms a covered deck; bold brick fireplace; exposed beam ceiling.'),
(5380,E'315 Highland Dr',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1968',E'Rambler with low-pitched roof arranged in wings off a central living area; vertical wood siding; beams extend to roof\'s overhangs; there\'s a brick fire place in the center of the living area.'),
(5381,E'341 Highland Dr',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'Dr. Bernard & Barbara Halper Residence',E'Unknown',E'1960',E'Combo rambler/split-level; wood siding in combination vertical and herringbone pattern; low-pitched roof with beams extending into overhangs; part of the front overhang forms a covered porch; interior was updated and opened up: original fireplace separating the dining area appears to have been altered slightly, though a granite surround appears to remain; Dr. Halper had served on the Board of the Minnesota Medical Foundation and a member of the Radiological Society of North America; the Halpers were involved in the Jewish community of the Iron Range: He had been president of the Agudath Achim Synagogue in Hibbing, Barbara was active in the Jewish Women of the Hibbing Chisholm Hadassah, which produced a series of cookbooks of Jewish cooking on the Iron Range, "Hot Off the Range."'),
(5382,E'451 Highland Dr',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Split-level with tuck-under garage and interesting supergraphics on the façade.'),
(5383,E'4220 3rd Ave W',E'Hibbing',E'MN',55746,NULL,NULL,E'Hibbing Alliance Church',E'Polivka, John',E'1967-68',E'Church and education wing built together; the church was persuaded to hire Polivka based on his work on the 1956 North Brook Alliance Church (6240 Aldrich Ave N, Brooklyn Center), and his knowledge of where to obtain "A" frame main beams at a cheaper price: the beams in the church “had been involved in a railroad crash on their way to delivery at the Northbrook Alliance Church building site and had been left out in the elements alongside the tracks where the crash occurred for an entire year. Their character and color is due to the fact they did sit out in the elements for a year, their quality was brought out with some sanding from a floor sander before use.”'),
(5384,E'1000 Lovell Ave W',E'Roseville',E'MN',55113,NULL,NULL,E'Rose of Sharon Nursing Home',E'Rev. A.V. Gustafson',E'1964-65',E'Two pastors of the Assemblies of God, Rev. Emmanuel A. Lundblad of Roseville\'s church (nearby) and architect and builder of Assembly of God churches, Rev. A.V. Gustafson, formed the Rose of Sharon, Inc., private corporation to build the $500,000 85-bed nursing home on 11-acres; the original rooms were decorated in either early-American, Italian provincial, and contemporary styles; it included a beauty shop, barber shop, physical therapy room with whirlpool baths, plus living, rec, and hobby rooms; as usual, Gustafson served also as the builder; Lundblad chose the name for three reasons “It’s in the Bible, the building is in Roseville, and Sharon is my wife’s name.”'),
(5385,E'202 7th Ave E',E'Alexandria',E'MN',56308,NULL,NULL,E'First Swedish Baptist Church',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Eventually renamed Cornerstone Church.'),
(5386,E'808 2nd Ave N',E'Fargo',E'ND',58102,NULL,NULL,E'Clark & Holman Building',E'Clark & Holman',E'1969',E'Two-story, modern brick office with simple modernist lines that featured an interior, long, skinny, 21-foot-tall atrium (45ft long, 8ft wide, lit by four 4-ft-sq skylights and reportedly once contained many plants); Perry S. Clark and Irvin C. Holman designed it as their office; Clark and Holman retired in and the firm, headed by younger partner Richard Moorhead, was renamed The Image Group and relocated to Moorhead, the building was then used as offices. Purchased by an admiring Fargo resident in 2008 and converted into his own house, working with architect Dave Uhlir; The conversion unfortunately took away some of the character of the building: many of the windows were removed (breaking up what had been a ribbon of windows spanning the façade on the upper floor), one of the two entrances now houses a garage.'),
(5387,E'215 5th St N',E'Fargo',E'ND',58102,NULL,NULL,E'Metropolitan Federal Savings & Loan Assn. building',E'Clark & Holman',E'1964',E'Received AIA North Dakota\'s First Honor Award (1966). '),
(5388,E'1330 S University Dr',E'Fargo',E'ND',58103,NULL,NULL,E'Olivet Lutheran Church',E'Sovik, Mathre & Madson',E'1965',E'Classic Sovik design: large, flexible main sanctuary creating a “non-church” for the people (who he saw as the “church”); this large complex includes a prominent, bold square bell tower topped by a Coptic cross, and the sides of the sanctuary have colored-glass windows set in four sizes of clay tile pipe embedded in concrete.'),
(5389,E'301 W Lyon St',E'Marshall',E'MN',56258,NULL,NULL,E'Marshall-Lyon County Library',E'Unknown',E'1966-67',E'The two-story structure was built on the same site as the original Carnegie Library and cost $300,000; in 2011 the library moved to a new structure, and in 2012, the Lyon County Board of Commissioners purchased the building for the Lyon County Historical Society.'),
(5390,E'407 12th St',E'Worthington',E'MN',56187,NULL,NULL,E'Nobles County War Memorial Building',E'Buetow & Assocs',E'1962-63',E'Prominent mid-century public building constructed 1962–63 to house a library branch, county historical society, and art center. A 1997 remodeling, including installation of the elevator, was sensitive to its design while resulting in needed updates. The building is apparently the only building erected specifically under Minnesota Statutes 1945, Section 373.053, which addressed war memorial construction at the close of World War II.  Listed on the National Register of Historic Places on June 5, 2017; its inclusion on the NRHP was more to do with its architectural merit.'),
(5391,E'1215 7th Ave',E'Worthington',E'MN',56187,NULL,NULL,E'Church of St. Mary',E'A. J. Ross & Assocs.',E'c.1960',E'Large thrust roof design, featured in a April 1961 ad in Progressive Architecture magazine (then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Marmet Corporation\'s aluminum church windows.'),
(5392,E'1645 S Shore Dr',E'Worthington',E'MN',56187,NULL,NULL,E'First Covenant Church',E'Unknown',E'1960-61',E'The facades have all been altered from earlier photos, and made much more mundane brick and plain pattern on the end of the sanctuary. The $90,000 project combined an auditorium and sanctuary, with fellowship and education facilities; designed to face the lake. Builder: Lindberg Contracting Co. (Boyden, IA). As of 2022: Living Waters Covenant Church.'),
(5393,E'224 Mary Ave',E'Springfield',E'MN',56087,NULL,NULL,E'St. Johns Lutheran Church',E'Unknown',E'1960',E'Straightforward A-frame church with educational wing.'),
(5394,E'101 Marshall Ave N',E'Springfield',E'MN',56087,NULL,NULL,E'Bank building',E'Unknown',E'1968',E'Brick with rounded corners; sits askew on the lot.'),
(5395,E'122 Central St W ',E'Springfield',E'MN',56087,NULL,NULL,E'Zion Lutheran Church',E'Unknown',E'1969',E'Church and educational wing; brick arches consistently featured in design, notable the belltower on the corner.'),
(5396,E'222 Pfau St',E'Mankato',E'MN',56001,NULL,NULL,E'Christ the King Lutheran Church',E'Rice & Schmidt Assoc.',E'1969',E'Original, 1960 phase included what is now a chapel, meeting room, office, and lobby; education wing added in 1964; the 1969 addition was substantial, bringing the current sanctuary as well as classrooms, offices, library, and more; 1995 remodeled and addition removed/replaced parts of the 1960 section.'),
