(5512,E'7840 County 17 Blvd',E'Cannon Falls',E'MN',55009,NULL,NULL,E'Pine Glen & Pachyderm Studios',E'Bloomberg, Herbert',E'1963',E'This house cannot be discussed without mentioning its eventual development into an important 1990s recording studio where many notable bands recorded albums such as Nirvana (In Utero), Soul Asylum (Grave Dancers Union), PJ Harvey (Rid of Me), Live (Throwing Copper), Babes in Toyland (Fontanelle), and many others. The house was originally built for Donald & Marian Mensing; Don worked for his father’s malt company, and hired architect Herb Bloomberg to design a house in town; Bloomberg (a developer best known for having designed the Chanhassen Dinner Theater) added many of his trademarks to the sprawling home: rustic brick exterior accented with wood; tongue and groove vaulted ceilings; expensive finishes: stone floors, stone walls, his avoidance of traditional square/rectangular rooms, as well as his love of indoor pools; after the Mensings passed, Jim Nickel bought the house and launched the Pachyderm Recording Studio in 1988 with co-founders Mark Walk and Eric S. Anderson, building a dedicated recording studio 50 yards from the house (the studio is actually three separate structures assembled next to each other to help control vibration); musicians would stay at Pine Glen (known as the Guest House) while recording at the studio; Nirvana bassist Krist Novoselic remembered liking the "Mike Brady kind of architecture" and said "It seemed good for Kurt [Cobain]\'s health"; financial duress led Nickel to sell the property in 2006, and it was mismanaged and allowed to become dilapidated before being rescued in a foreclosure sale by reputable Twin Cities studio operator John Kuker in 2011; Kuker’s 2011-14 renovation brought the house back into good condition and restored the interior to period style; he unexpectedly died in February 2015, age 40, and it was sold again.'),
