(5561,E'333 Smith Ave N',E'St Paul',E'MN',55102,NULL,NULL,E'St. Luke\'s Hospital',E'Ellerbe Associates',E'1960-61',E'The "cloverleaf" design for the 3 towers based on Ellerbe\'s design for the experimental unit (1957) at Rochester Methodist Hospital (now part of the Mayo Clinic): by 1960, Ellerbe\'s chief of hospital design, Edwin Larson, said the circular tower design was "the latest step forward in handling the problem of hospital cost" noting that the Methodist Hospital showed "three years of experimental operation with 12 patients requiring constant nursing care reveals that hospitals can save more than half the nursing cost for patients who need constant care. You can\'t handle more than about 30 to 35 patients in a single circle. [. . .] The secret is concentrating actual patient care in the circle. Extra services like the kitchens, teaching space, elevators and the rest are outside this patient circle. So the nurse is not distracted by noise or walking distance normal in a hospital. The circle plan means either better care or fewer nurses--there\'s no question about that." Ellerbe meanwhile employed the design for the full Rochester Methodist Hospital (1963-66), Ancker Hospital (now Region\'s) in St. Paul (1963-65) and added a similar circular addition (though smaller) to Lakeview Hospital in Stillwater; the hospital won a design award, and 4 floors were added 8 years after construction; in 1972, St Luke\'s and nearby Charles T. Miller Hospital consolidated to form United Hospital, using the physical campus of Saint Luke\'s; major addition in 1976-80 constructed a new hospital to be partially shared with Children\'s Hospital-St. Paul; a major 1989-91 addition added a $22M project for ambulatory surgery, radiation therapy and the Ritchie Medical Plaza.'),
(5562,E'801 8th Ave',E'Howard Lake',E'MN',55349,NULL,NULL,E'Howard Lake School (add\'n)',E'Unknown',E'1966*',E'The 1954 addition was Hammel & Green\'s first project on its way to becoming HGA; there were subsequent additions in 1966 and 1976 (gym and classroom addition on north side); in 2015-16 most of the school was demolished, including the original and 1956 additions (with a small 2016 addition to cap off the south end). Unclear if HGA had involvement in the later additions.'),
