(5571,E'1305 W 18th St',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57117,NULL,NULL,E'Sioux Valley Hospital (add\'n)',E'Ellerbe Architects',E'1969-73',E'Firm retained in 1966 for what was initially planned as a massive, 3-phase $17M project, with associate architects Friztel, Kroeger, Griffin and Berg (Sioux Falls); for Phase I, Ellerbe, known for work in hospitals since developing the Mayo Clinic, created what was known as the Penta Plan to solve the complicated program of this project: the administrators projected a high patient population on a somewhat limited site, and as a general hospital it would address patients requiring a wide spectrum of care; the 5, linear wings in a star fashion from a central nursing station and supply core allowed it to provide the required number of beds with visible units immediately around the nursing core and intermediate or minimal care rooms arranged along the corridors of the radiating wings; 4 of the 5 wings contain patients, with the remaining "spoke" containing service elements for each floor.'),
(5572,E'1421 Elton Hills Dr NW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55901,NULL,NULL,E'Elton Hills Elementary School',E'Ellerbe & Co.',E'1960',E'Prototype design for an inexpensive, flexible elementary school consisting of a series of classrooms connected to a large multi-purpose room (which could serve as auditorium, lecture hall, activity space, and cafeteria); the larger room was surrounded by a corridor for access to the classrooms. This design was then used for 6 schools in Rochester alone, as well as others in Minnesota and Wisconsin; Addition in 1966. '),
(5573,E'425 Ranchview Ln N',E'Plymouth',E'MN',55447,NULL,NULL,E'Birchview Elementary School',E'Ellerbe Architects',E'1969',E'Prototype design featuring an open classroom concept that was popularized in the 1960s; the planning team consisted of a principal and five teachers who would be teaching in the new school; an early plan envisioned one, large open complex with 12 teaching areas, but it was judged too radical; per Thomas F. Ellerbe, the initial design instead consisted of "four sections of each grade level in an open area (or pod, as the area came to be called) with six pods in all. Teacher preparation centers were built in each area. The goal behind this design was to enable each student to learn at his or her own pace utilizing more personalized teaching. The floor plan was the shape of a triangle with a triangular resource center at the heart of the building. The resource center was surrounded by five rectangular sections - on two sides by the primary and intermediate classroom wings and on a third side by the administrative section." The classroom pods employ moveable partitions that permit flexible, programmable spaces. Designed at the same time as the district administration building at 210 Cty Rd 101.'),
(5574,E'1300 40th St NW',E'Rochester',E'MN',55901,NULL,NULL,E'Gage Elementary School',E'Ellerbe Architects',E'1965',E'Based on the prototype Ellerbe developed with the Elton Hills Elementary School (1960) for an inexpensive, flexible elementary school consisting of a series of classrooms connected to a large multi-purpose room (which could serve as auditorium, lecture hall, activity space, and cafeteria); the larger room was surrounded by a corridor for access to the classrooms. This design was then used for 6 schools in Rochester alone, as well as others in Minnesota and Wisconsin. Subsequent addition.'),
