(5601,E'300 22nd Ave S',E'Brookings',E'SD',57006,NULL,NULL,E'Brookings Hospital',E'Ellerbe & Co.',E'1963-64',E'2-story structure using the Radial Plan that Ellerbe developed with the Mayo Clinic or an experimental unit (1957) at Rochester Methodist Hospital: by 1960, Ellerbe\'s chief of hospital design, Edwin Larson, said the circular design was "the latest step forward in handling the problem of hospital cost" noting that the Methodist Hospital showed "three years of experimental operation with 12 patients requiring constant nursing care reveals that hospitals can save more than half the nursing cost for patients who need constant care. You can\'t handle more than about 30 to 35 patients in a single circle. [. . .] The secret is concentrating actual patient care in the circle. Extra services like the kitchens, teaching space, elevators and the rest are outside this patient circle. So the nurse is not distracted by noise or walking distance normal in a hospital. The circle plan means either better care or fewer nurses--there\'s no question about that." Ellerbe meanwhile employed the design for the full Rochester Methodist Hospital (1963-66), and 3-tower (Cloverleaf) versions for Ancker Hospital (now Region\'s) and St Luke (now United Hospital) in St. Paul and a similar circular version at Lakeview Hospital in Stillwater; this shorter, 61-bed hospital replaced a 1907 structure, and has had additions in 1989, 2009, and beyond. A sketch and floorplan of the initial design was featured in an October 1956 ad (in the AIA Journal) for Hillyard Floor Treatments.'),
(5602,E'109 S 7th St',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55402,NULL,NULL,E'Roanoke Building (add\'n/remodel)',E'Baker-Lange Associates',E'1963-64',E'Major addition more than doubling useable space: The tower portion of the 1927 building originally only took up half of the footprint (with the lower three levels extending full length), but after Investors Diversified Services (lDS) signed a then-landmark, $25M, 24yr deal with property owner Baker Properties (the $1.122M per year lease was a record in the Twin Cities), the Baker Properties agreed to a $2.5M major expansion to have the tower extend to fill the entire property (IDS also took a significant minority stake in company Baker Properties set up to own the building); the addition added 90,000sf to the existing 75,000sf; cornices and projecting molding from the original section were replaced with modern trim; interior work was Larson & McLaren; Builder: Naugle-Leck, Inc.'),
