(5625,E'2655 Chicago Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55407,NULL,NULL,E'Northwestern Hospital (add\'n)',E'Ellerbe & Co.',E'1962-63',E'Major, $3.6M addition on the north side of the original building, featuring the Radial Plan that Ellerbe developed for the experimental unit (1957) at Rochester Methodist Hospital (now part of the Mayo Clinic): by 1960, Ellerbe\'s chief of hospital design, Edwin Larson, said the circular tower design was "the latest step forward in handling the problem of hospital cost" noting that the Methodist Hospital showed "three years of experimental operation with 12 patients requiring constant nursing care reveals that hospitals can save more than half the nursing cost for patients who need constant care. You can\'t handle more than about 30 to 35 patients in a single circle. [. . .] The secret is concentrating actual patient care in the circle. Extra services like the kitchens, teaching space, elevators and the rest are outside this patient circle. So the nurse is not distracted by noise or walking distance normal in a hospital. The circle plan means either better care or fewer nurses--there\'s no question about that." Ellerbe meanwhile employed the design for Lakeview Hospital in Stillwater (1959-61), St. Luke\'s Hospital (now United) in St. Paul (1960-61), and Ancker Hospital (now Region\'s) in St. Paul; by the time it was implemented in the full Rochester Methodist Hospital (1963-66) and here for Northwestern (now Abbott Northwestern), the footprint was an octagon rather than a curved circle; the original plan was for only 4-floors of the radial plan (it became 6, the design was expandable), which took the hospital\'s capacity from 270 to 390; the rest of the addition included clinical lab, new X-ray dept; emergency room, pharmacy, kitchen & cafeteria, OR, and recovery rooms; Builder: M.A. Mortenson. The original hospital wing (with U-shaped tower) originally fronted 810 27th St E, but that portion of the street was removed as the hospital later expanded south. It merged with Abbott Hospital in 1971 to become Abbott Northwestern on what was originally the Northwestern Hospital campus.'),
