(5643,E'252 Marie Ave E',E'West St Paul',E'MN',55118,NULL,NULL,E'Westview Park',E'Community Planning & Design Assoc.',E'1960-70',E'In an awkward reality of planning, this L-shaped, 110-acre development received a 1961 Citation from Progressive Architecture magazine (then the biggest magazine on modernism) in their annual Design Awards Program (jury: Charles R. Colbert (chair), O\'Neil Ford, Philip C. Johnson, Walter A. Netsch, Jr., Chloethiel Woodard Smith), but narrowly tailored to the design of a small shopping center on the NW corner that was unrealized over the course of actual development (it would\'ve that would have used prestressed-concrete slabs on prestressed-concrete beams in a very simple but elegant horizontal composition). Hence the Citation is for the project Service Commercial Center for "Westview Park Company." The actual submission to P/A was the overall Westview Park development, which responded to a program for "A well-planned industrial park was considered necessary to attract desirable industry and commerce to the area." The design opted for what they deemed a parklike design with 5 classifications of land use, noting "Height restrictions, architecture, land coverage, preservation of trees, as well as controlled loading, setback and off-street parking are designed for functional efficiency and preservation of the pleasant surroundings." The citation specifically credited architects Dennis W. Grebner, Thomas H. Hodne, and Reynold M. Roberts, as well as planner Robert Isaacson; Structural Engineers: Johnson-Sahlman Co; Mechanical Engineers: J.T. Baker & Assoc. While the general street layout was followed, the plan for what filled in those blocks quickly fell apart: what was original set for offices and light industrial in the SE corner (below Marie Ave and west of Oakdale) was made part of a larger multi-family development that had only be planned for the section bordering the eastern strip of pre-existing houses (now Westview Dr.); a park planned at the inside elbow was never developed in any of the imagery from 1965-71; similarly, the plan for multi-family housing north of the existing residential (Kathleen Dr for reference) and south of Marie Ave was swapped with light industrial. The spot reserved for the touted Service Commercial Center became industrial, and later demolished and replaced with a large Target store.'),
(5644,E'219 2nd St N',E'Sartell',E'MN',56377,NULL,NULL,E'St. Francis Xavier High School',E'B. J. Knowles & Co.',E'1960',E'Low, single-story school that originally featured glass block windows alongside the dramatic exterior panels of granite; featured in a March 1961 ad (in Progressive Architecture) for heating and ventilating systems by Norman Products Co.; has had additions and remodeling.'),
(5645,E'301 2nd St SW',E'Stewartville',E'MN',55976,NULL,NULL,E'Stewartville Elementary School (add\'n)',E'Patch & Erickson',E'1963-64',E'After locals previously 3-times rejected the award-winning, $490,000 stand-alone school (1960 P/A Design Award citation) by Adkins & Johnson, the voters eventually approved this $395,000 elementary school addition on the south side of the existing school gym, with a corridor joining the two structures; the addition was designed with 13 classrooms, 2 kindergarten rooms, remedial reading room, library, cafeteria, office area, A/V room, etc.; construction was beset with a labor dispute, but it mostly opened on schedule; Builder: Century Const. (Preston). Later renamed the Central Education Center.'),
