(5650,E'7210 MN-61',E'Tofte',E'MN',55615,NULL,NULL,E'Olsen\'s Motel & Gift Shop',E'Unknown',E'c.1960',E'Given a mention in Larry Millet\'s 2015 book "Minnesota Modern," the small building combines a swooping Googie, upthrust roof with more rustic gray brick; although the original, 30-unit motel was demolished and replaced with a modern resort (Bluefin Bay), this building was wisely kept.'),
(5651,E'1501 W 26th St',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57105,NULL,NULL,E'Christ the King Catholic Church',E'Howard Parezo & Associates',E'1961-62',E'Featured in a December 1963 ad (in Progressive Architecture) by DuPont as an example of the creative roofs that can be protected using their Neoprene and Hypalon synthetic rubber products. Designed with a capacity of 800. Exterior of church in gray Cold Spring granite and steel-reinforced concrete form; interior also uses granite, with polished Carthage marble structural columns of gray-brown tones, and a ceiling in white plaster (54ft nave); the east side of the interior features white split-faced Georgian marble as the background for a 24-foot, dark-stained oak cross mounted with a cast-aluminum figure of Jesus Christ with the plain polished granite altar in front of it (there are narrow side windows providing light to the altar area); flanking the sanctuary are serpentine curving walls of gray granite brick latticework for the side altars; predominantly white Venetian terrazzo floors; on the west end is a baptismal font in polished black and deep gray granite, the west wall is dominated by a full-height (54’x15’) stained glass window on the western end, with a giant cross formed by two steel beams doubling as structural supports: when lit from the interior, the window creates a bold impact on the exterior during the evening; the stained glass was designed by University of Notre Dame art prof. Robert Leader (1924-2006) and conveys the Creation of the World from the Book of Genesis, as Leader noted "I wanted something of cosmic proportions to take place when a viewer would behold this window." The stained glass was cut and assembled by the Reinart Stained Glass Studio in Winona, MN. Rectory, connected to the SE corner, constructed with gray wood and granite.'),
(5652,E'1101 E 1st St',E'Webster',E'SD',57274,NULL,NULL,E'Christ the King Catholic Church',E'Ralph Koch Architects',E'1966',E'Sioux Falls-based firm; credited specifically to Ralph R. Koch. Circular shape with steep, pointy roof topped with a slightly abstract crown (matched by the bell tower); per research by the site History in South Dakota, "the design was chosen to draw eyes towards the altar and to reflect the tents of the Old Testament, which were places to encounter God." The actual seating arrangement is a fan shape; the interior makes use of a lot of stained glass clerestory windows where the round roof sits on the brick base (using the thick, curved engineered wood beams to divide them).'),
