(5657,E'8230 47th Ave N',E'New Hope',E'MN',55428,NULL,NULL,E'E. J. Cooper Senior High School',E'Bissell, Belair & Green',E'1963-64',E'The pair of round wings were a part of the original structure\'s design, built with reinforced concrete and masonry; the connecting corridors featured a mix of masonry and glass block walls to have softly diffused daylight; the corridor was featured in a February 1965 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Pittsburgh Corning\'s PC Intaglio Glass Wall Units; Renamed "Robbinsdale Cooper" to placate residents of Robbinsdale after the consolidation of 3 district high schools between New Hope and Robbinsdale led Robbinsdale High School to close. '),
(5658,E'15251 Pleasant Valley Rd',E'Center City',E'MN',55012,NULL,NULL,E'Hazelden Rehabilitation Center',E'Voigt & Fourre',E'1964-66',E'Received "Award of Merit" for distinguished architecture at the 32nd Annual Convention of the Minnesota Society of Architects (1966): judges cited "The busy silhouette and plan are appropriate counterpoints for the surrounding calm." Featured in the August 1965 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism), as an example of modern approach to institutional buildings. The program was a treatment center for alcoholics, to consolidate and expand several, with total residential capacity of 125 (100 were new) with common facilities for dining and group activities as well as library, chapel, and some shopping facilities. This architectural program was complicated by the need to meet the core of the Hazelden residential rehabilitation program: daily individual and group sessions of therapy and discussion, with success stemming from its small numbers, "peer-group therapy," and casual atmosphere--thus the organization wanted to still keep patients in groups of 18-20 and avoid seeming "too large. too impersonal. too institutionalized." The feature in P/A summarized the need for a new approach: "The alcoholic is sometimes very ill physically for a short time. \'but we don\'t want a hospital.\' Many of them are emotionally disturbed, \'but we don\'t want a mental hospital.\' Many need spiritual help, \'but we don\'t want a church.\' In some ways, they said, \'we want a hotel or motel atmosphere, but that isn\'t exactly it, either; in some ways we want a residential club.\'" The solution was a design meant to evoke a "hill village" (with a variety of placement, views, and elevations) that would keep an intimate scale for the individual, while making them feel like a part of a community. Residence units were built around the 18-22 patient therapeutic unit, with some common areas overlooking a central court; the architects envisioned each of the "therapy units" having "an integral form" that "becomes a neighborhood within the total community." Site drops 50ft to lake, the structures used masonry bearing-wall construction, with concrete slab on grade and precast-concrete roof deck; exteriors of red face brick for exterior walls with brick and lightweight concrete block for interior walls and limited use of vertical oak boards for partitions; total cost of the project was estimated at $1,400,000; Structural engineers: Schuett-Meier Co.; Mechanical engineers: Gausman & Moore, Inc. Many subsequent additions on the 100-acre site. Renamed the Hazelden Betty Ford Foundation after the merger of the two organizations in 2014.'),
(5659,E'505 4th St NE',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55413,NULL,NULL,E'St Michael\'s Ukrainian Orthodox Church (add\'n)',E'Gingold-Pink',E'1967-68',E'Brutalist community room addition to the side of a 1925-26 church; Builder: Kloster-Madson, Inc.'),
(5660,E'501 Royalston Ave N',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55405,NULL,NULL,E'Northwest Automatic Products Corporation',E'S. C. Smiley and Associates',E'1962-63',E'With Donald Hustad. The building is notably for its engineering as the country\'s first ductless direct-fire heating system, the HVAC system was subject of a detailed article in the November 1965 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism), noting that the rooftop furnaces cut down fuel costs while eliminated ducts and maintaining heat, "gas consumption for heating was less than half what Minnesota Gas Company engineers had predicted" while also achieving "double the expected performance." "Since this was the first installation of its kind, gas company engineers recommended two furnace units. To be on the safe side, however, the company installed three. Yet in the first winter, just one unit was sufficient to handle both the factory and the office building when outside temperatures dropped to -18 F.  [. . .] With no experience to draw on, gas company engineers estimated heating costs at $10,000 for the 1,800,000-cu-ft factory. For the first winter-with the building unfinished, no windows installed, and no heating system for the office-- heating cost was only $4,000." The 100,000sf factor contained 100 automatic screw machines, plus dozens of milling and drilling machines, lathes, grinders, deburrers, punch presses, and heat-treating furnaces. The $1.5M, one-story building was developed in the Glenwood Renewal Area to replace the original building at 1700 Linden Ave (demolished for the freeway); the build address was originally 555 Olson Blvd.'),
(5661,E'109 E 6th St',E'Starbuck',E'MN',56381,NULL,NULL,E'U. S. Post Office',E'Unknown',E'c.1960s',E'"Thousand Series" Post Office. Part of the major shift in how the U.S. Postal Service operated in the post-War era: To expand quickly, the Post Office pushed a $1.5 billion privately financed lease-purchase program with local developers. Design brochures developed by the Post Office Department in the late 1950s and early 1960s guided the contract-built "Thousand Series" small post offices around the country (the name refers to building size: 1,000-12,000 sf). After sites were determined, the lease-purchase program would select developers through a competitive bid process based on the lowest bid. Bidders would choose designs from the U.S Postal Service\'s 1959 "Building Design" brochure, which stressed modernity and convenience over regional identity or the role of the federal government in everyday life. The resulting buildings were usually not designed by architects, but by the construction contractor using the brochure renderings and guidelines for reference. The brochure offered "acceptable" designs, with Postmaster General Arthur Summerfield asserting his desire that post offices be built as Modern buildings focusing on efficiency and clean lines. The International Style was predominant, calling mostly for flat roofs, exterior wall materials of aluminum or stainless-steel framed window walls with stone, face brick, or precast concrete. The brochures noted that the designs were adaptable to many variations and site characteristics, and because exterior design and materials could be adjusted to suit local conditions, suitable for all climates and geographical areas in the United States. While the designs were easy for local builders and contractors to follow, the lack of an architect in the construction process did affect the design quality of the completed building, and often resulted in small post offices that were a-contextual and stylistically homogeneous (emphasizing economy over creativity). There was notably no emphasis on landscaping. The topic is explored in the "USPS Nationwide Historic Context Study: Postal Facilities Constructed or Occupied Between 1940 and 1971" (URS Group, Inc. prepared for U.S. Postal Service, September 2012.).'),
