(5668,E'3955 Washington Ave SE',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55455,NULL,NULL,E'Washington Avenue Bridge',E'Engineers: Sverdrup & Parcel',E'1965',E'[placeholder address] Double-decker, 1130ft county-owned bridge originally carrying a major street (Washington Ave, 2 lanes in either direction) below and pedestrians on top; later altered to carry light rail traffic on the car deck by eliminating one of the traffic lanes on both sides. A primary purpose was connecting the two sides of the University of Minnesota’s Minneapolis campus after the development of what became known as the West Bank began in the early 1960s; also significant for its innovative engineering techniques. It three main spans, which are continuous welded haunched steel girders of 246ft, 315ft, and 246ft; bridge was one of the first in the nation to use A441 high-strength, low-alloy steel in its superstructure, which allowed for the structure to be welded rather than riveted. Bridge is supported by reinforced-concrete piers. Both levels are 74ft wide, the upper pedestrian deck features an enclosed walkway that is 30 ft wide and 8 ft high, extending the length of the bridge. To better integrate the bridge with the surrounding academic buildings on both sides, it features globe street lamps lining each side of the upper deck, railing, integrated staircases, plaza areas at each end of the bridge, and stylistic pedestrian enclosure featuring large glass walls. The design process that led up to the current bridge was begun in 1954 by Ralph Rapson, the recently-appointed Dean of the UMN\'s School of Architecture, who had students analyze the university\'s expansion needs and offer solutions; of 4 proposals presented to the administration in 1955, the one ultimately selected "recommended that the university expand across the Mississippi River with a \'Ponte Vecchio-like bridge\' connecting the existing east campus and a new west campus. Vehicular traffic would be on the lower level and pedestrians above. The lower level would connect with a tunnel on the east riverbank to Oak Street to make the campus free of through traffic." The UMN Board of Regents adopted the West Bank plan in 1957, and East Bank buildings began being designed to anticipate the pedestrian upper level of the bridge; preliminary plans were drawn in 1960, and soon adapted to use the A441 steel which permitted a leaner design. Originally the enclosure was envisioned in the Ponte Vecchio concept as a gallery space that would house bookstalls, information and ticket booths, and various types of exhibits, but was never implemented because the bridge was at its maximum dead-load capacity. Lower deck opened in 1965, upper deck in 1966. Featured in a January 1968 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for the Mississippi Glass Company, which provided the glazing for the covered walkway which used a quarter-mile "life safe" Polished MISCO Wire (22,300 ft.) for both fire retardance and impact resistance. Designing engineers based in St. Louis (MO); Builder: Walter Giertsen Co.; also referred to by MnDOT as Bridge 9360. Originally a light metallic gray, the bridge was painted the maroon of the University of Minnesota with a gold band on the walkway roof. In the 1970s, the lower glass panes were replaced with wooden panels that were painted by various student organizations. Rehabbed in 2011-13, primarily to accommodate the new Central Corridor Light Rail transit line: 2 lines of Warren trusses were added between the original plate girders and 2 additional pier columns were added to accommodate the additional loads on the bridge; the design was sympathetic and done to minimize visual impacts and maintain the design aesthetic of the original structure. It remains the only double-decker bridge in Minnesota.'),
(5669,E'670 Robert St N',E'St Paul',E'MN',55101,NULL,NULL,E'Emma Norton Methodist Girls\' Residence',E'Progressive Design Associates',E'1966-67',E'Originally founded in 1917 as the Methodist Home for Girls, young women traveling to the Twin Cities from rural Minnesota for work and education; it was founded with a gift by Emma Norton to the United Methodist Women, and the new building ($400,000) was named in her honor. Featured in a March 1968 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for windows by the Anderson Corporation; in August \'68 the company greatly increased the size of their feature on the building\'s use of their Perma-Shield (low maintenance) windows..'),
