(5679,E'3 Birdie Ln',E'Chaska',E'MN',55318,NULL,NULL,E'Mr. & Mrs. Totton "Tot" Peavey Heffelfinger Residence',E'Bloomberg, Herbert',E'1967',E'Heffelfinger was the president of Hazeltine National Golf Club from 1959 to 1972. Bloomberg was asked to "design their home so it would harmonize with the surroundings" ; who was notably also hired to design the original Hazeltine clubhouse… Over time, the clubhouse became a bit of an eyesore and was a source of some embarrassment to club management, it was replaced in 2010. Heffelfinger was a driving force in the effort to create Hazeltine in the late \'50s, he loved golf and Hazeltine and was a driving force in the effort to land a major golf tournament (the breakthrough being the 1970 U.S. Open Golf Championship as well as the U.S. Women\'s Open in 1966 and 1977). He was rankled when the course received criticism from golfers during the 1970 tournament, he reduced his involvement in the club. His business career began as a buyer in several grain companies; by 1946, he was president of the Van Dusen Harrington Co. of Minneapolis and in 1959 became president of the Peavey Co. after it had merged with Harrington. Heffelfinger died in 1987, age 88; the next owner of the house was lawyer Reed Mackenzie, a member of Hazeltine since 1965, who eventually became president of Hazeltine and general chairman of the U.S. Open in 1991, when the event was once again played at Hazelton.  Mackenzie jokingly claimed 3 Birdie Lane is haunted by the spirit of Tot!'),
(5680,E'56 6th St E',E'St Paul',E'MN',55101,NULL,NULL,E'Skyway Building',E'Grover Dimond Assoc.',E'1969',E'The epitome of "what could have been": The Skyway Building was intended to be a three-block-long "omnibuilding" that bridged two streets (Cedar and Minnesota Sts) and formed the symbolic backbone of the Capitol Centre, a 12-block urban redevelopment area, started by St. Paul\'s Housing Redevelopment Authority (HRA) in the 1950s in conjunction with the Architects\' Counseling Committee (consisting of 4 firms: Cavin & Page, Cerny Assoc., Grover Dimond Assoc., and Haarstick, Lundgren & Assoc.). When construction was announced in the May 1969 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism), it was noted as a $6,500,000, 5-story structure that would contain 100,000 sq ft of commercial space and parking space for 1200 cars, with "more floors to be added later." Importantly, it would serve as a major section of the St. Paul Skyway System being designed by HGA, connecting 6 adjacent blocks; it was designed to include a metal curtain walls and screens to harmonize with the adjacent Northwestern National Bank building, also designed by Grover Dimond Assoc. The 3 blocks it was supposed to span were planned in 1965 as part of $26.8M development with Davidson-Baker Company (now anchored by the Osborn buildings, Northwestern National Bank building, and American National Bank building). The Skyway Building and Northwestern National Bank building were developed by the bank and Chicago-based L.J. Sheridan Co. In the end, it was only over 2 blocks (crossing only Cedar) and became mostly a parking garage with limited street-level retail. No planned additional levels were added. The original Skyway Building name has been supplanted by merely being known as the parking garage for the adjacent buildings. '),
(5681,E'410 Groveland Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55403,NULL,NULL,E'Summit House Condominiums ',E'Gingold-Pink',E'1966-67',E'The East Tower (build 1968-69) featured in a May 1969 ad (in Progressive Architecture) for Armco Steel\'s "Tufwire" strands, used with pre-tensioning prestressed concrete in the 27-story towers. Permit in \'66 (with Paul M. Pink on form); developed by Ruttan-Minnesota Inc. (a division of Ruttan Investment Corporation, ltd., Winnipeg, Manitoba); Structural Engineer: Crosier, Greenberg & Partners (Winnipeg, MB); Builder: Bor-Son Const. Co.'),
(5682,E'400 Groveland Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55403,NULL,NULL,E'Summit House East ',E'Gingold-Pink',E'1968-69',E'Featured in a May 1969 ad (in Progressive Architecture) for Armco Steel\'s "Tufwire" strands, used with pre-tensioning prestressed concrete in the 27-story towers. Permit in \'66 (with Paul M. Pink on form); developed by Ruttan-Minnesota Inc. (a division of Ruttan Investment Corporation, ltd., Winnipeg, Manitoba); Structural Engineer: Crosier, Greenberg & Partners (Winnipeg, MB); Builder: Bor-Son Const. Co.'),
(5683,E'1400 73rd Ave NE',E'Fridley',E'MN',55432,NULL,NULL,E'Onan Headquarters & Manufacturing Complex',E'Engineer: Walter Kidde Constructors',E'1967-69',E'The large complex replaced the previous, large facility on University Ave near the University of Minnesota; 147-acre site was purchased in 1967; 456,200sf plant, 85,000sf 3-story office building, 57,640sf one-story engineering building. Walter Kidde Constructors, Inc. was a New York based company that began in construction (including acting as Designers-Engineers) and eventually pivoted to fire suppression systems. Originally slated for $8M, the complex ended up costing $15M as it was expected to generate $50M a year in revenue as it built electric power plants, air cooled engines, separate generators and automatic controls. Featured in a May 1970 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Hillyard floor treatments. Builder: Watson Const. Co.; major expansions. The Onan Company was founded in 1922 and became a major player in electric generator sets; it was sold to Studebaker-Packard in 1960 (the combined car manufacturers were in the process of diversifying and exiting auto manufacturing); by 1967 the company name was relegated to "Onan Division of Studebaker Corp." Studebaker later became Studebaker-Worthington Corp., and considered moving the Studebaker Corp. holding company to the new Fridley facility from the main headquarters in South Bend, Indiana. Onan was purchased by the Cummins Engine Company in 1992, eventually rebranded Cummins Power Systems.'),
(5684,E'141 N Main Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57104,NULL,NULL,E'National Bank of South Dakota Building',E'Harold Spitznagel & Associates',E'1963-65',E'10-story office building; Later renamed US Bank Building.'),
(5685,E'101 2nd St',E'Fargo',E'ND',58103,NULL,NULL,E'Lashkowitz High Rise',E'Trossen, Wright & Prokasky',E'1968-70',E'At 22-story, 250-unit tower has the most floors of any building in Fargo, but was beat for height (204 to 207ft) by the Radisson Hotel Fargo in 1985 (but it only has 18 floors); it is the tallest residential building in the state; it may be the tallest building ever constructed with the lift-slab method. Part of a May 1970 feature in Progressive Architecture (P/A, then the biggest magazine on modernism) on "The Architect...In the Business of Developing" and how the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development\'s Turnkey Housing Program inadvertently influenced the trend towards the architect-developer by finding that architects who act as developers on Turnkey projects turn out "better-than-average" housing--resulting in HUD urging district offices "to use architects as developers whenever possible." "Trossen, Wright, and Prokasky (TWP) \'recognized the increasing demands for procedural changes in the practice of architecture.\' The firm subsequently formed the Ithaca Corporation with Lovering Construction Co. to plan, design, and build low-cost housing for the elderly in Fargo, North Dakota, and Madison, South Dakota. [. . .] TWP maintains a majority interest in the corporation \'to assure its professional design and client service-oriented character. \' Projects are initially planned and designed by the architectural staff. Upon establishment of a planning concept, the estimating and construction staff determine costs, construction materials, and techniques. Typical building sections and an outline specification are developed, the final price is itemized, and the proposal submitted to the client. A principal architect remains the arbitrator and executor throughout the evolution of the project." Structural Engineers: Foss, Engelstad & Foss. In 2019, the Fargo Housing and Redevelopment Authority announced HUD, which oversees the building, determined the building had many structural issues over the years, was damaged by a fire the prior winter, and was no longer worth maintaining; it is scheduled for demolition and replacement with a low-rise mixed-use building.'),
(5686,E'111 Washington Ave S',E'Madison',E'SD',57042,NULL,NULL,E'Lakeview Tower',E'Trossen, Wright & Prokasky',E'1969-70',E'The 12-story tower dominates the skyline of Madison, and the tallest building in South Dakota outside of Sioux Falls and Rapid City. Included as part of a May 1970 feature in Progressive Architecture (P/A, then the biggest magazine on modernism) on "The Architect...In the Business of Developing" and how the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development\'s Turnkey Housing Program inadvertently influenced the trend towards the architect-developer by finding that architects who act as developers on Turnkey projects turn out "better-than-average" housing--resulting in HUD urging district offices "to use architects as developers whenever possible." "Trossen, Wright, and Prokasky (TWP) \'recognized the increasing demands for procedural changes in the practice of architecture.\' The firm subsequently formed the Ithaca Corporation with Lovering Construction Co. to plan, design, and build low-cost housing for the elderly in Fargo, North Dakota, and Madison, South Dakota. [. . .] TWP maintains a majority interest in the corporation \'to assure its professional design and client service-oriented character. \' Projects are initially planned and designed by the architectural staff. Upon establishment of a planning concept, the estimating and construction staff determine costs, construction materials, and techniques. Typical building sections and an outline specification are developed, the final price is itemized, and the proposal submitted to the client. A principal architect remains the arbitrator and executor throughout the evolution of the project."'),
(5687,E'7705 Bush Lake Rd',E'Edina',E'MN',55439,NULL,NULL,E'Carleton Screw Products Co.',E'Bell, Bryce E.',E'1968-69',E'All-concrete plant and office for local light industrial manufacturer with eye-catching pattern. Featured in a June 1970 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for the Lehigh Cements, boasting the lower insurance premiums that would make up the increased upfront cost "in about four to five years." Designer: Kaye Westerlund; Engineer: James Swensen; Builder: C.O. Field Co.'),
(5688,E'626 Shields Ave',E'Wabasha',E'MN',55981,NULL,NULL,E'Wabasha Nursing Home',E'Korsunsky-Krank',E'1969-70',E'Opened with capacity for 125 patients and featured 4 day rooms, barber shop, beauty shop, laundry, and therapy rooms, 3 bedroom areas (by patient classification), and separate patient and staff dining areas. Featured in a December 1970 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Armco Steel\'s prestressed concrete. Builder: Keller Construction Co. (Hudson, WI); As of 2021 it is named Gundersen St. Elizabeth\'s Care Center Shields Ave.'),
(5689,E'808 Winneshiek Rd',E'La Crosse',E'WI',54603,NULL,NULL,E'Mullen Homes',E'Hackner Schroeder Roslansky & Associates (HSR)',E'c.1968',E'Received AIA Wisconsin Design Award; public townhouses developed for the La Cross Housing Authority were cited for use of materials that added "dignity and distinction" to low-cost housing; sadly, the most interesting aspect (vertical wood boards in a raw finish) were replaced at some point with cheap-looking horizontal siding, undercutting the entire point of the design. Featured in an April 1971 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Andersen Windows.'),
(5690,E'1712 Randolph Ave',E'St Paul',E'MN',55105,NULL,NULL,E'St Paul Academy & Summit School (add\'n)',E'Benjamin Thompson & Assoc.',E'1969-71',E'Built shortly after the merger of two schools in 1969 (all-boys St. Paul Academy and all-girls Summit School), it was featured in the March 1972 issue of Progressive Architecture (then the biggest magazine on modernism), which highlighted how Thompson\'s role not only design the addition, but helped plan their merger into one co-ed institution: "The merger of two tradition-minded prep schools provides an example of new math: one tradition plus another gives another totally new tradition, plus a forward looking school." The firm served as educational consultant for the changeover to an immediate shift to co-education; Thompson\'s staff included Henry Olds (PhD in education) who worked closely with administration and faculty during architectural planning and fund raising. The phased project involved $1.8M and 70,000sf of new construction and $500,000 to renovate 47,040sf of renovated space. This (the original St. Paul Academy campus) was converted into the combined Upper School, while the Summit School campus became the lower school. The new upper school was planned around a central landscaped courtyard that provides an enclosed landscape of trees and grass. In the first phase (1969), one existing building was demolished, then the existing main building was remodeled. The second phase (1970) added a mechanical services building, gym addition, new library, and living center. The design grouped them into two-story buildings that open directly onto the central court. Other major additions included a Learning Center and Science/Mathematics Addition; all are modular structures with exposed concrete frames and infilling of white painted brick and glass; Thompson (1918-2002) was born and spend his early years in St Paul, including as a student of St. Paul Academy, before moving to New England where he later co-founded The Architects Collaborative in 1945; Associate architects: Wold Assoc.; Structural Engineers: Bakke & Kopp, Inc.; mechanical and electrical engineers, Gausman & Moore, Inc. This addition is now surrounded by other additions, but is visible from a courtyard they frame.'),
(5691,E'4050 Coon Rapids Blvd NW',E'Coon Rapids',E'MN',55433,NULL,NULL,E'Mercy Hospital',E'Unknown',E'1963-64',E'The 150-bed, $1,833,000 hospital was built as a joint venture of the Anoka-Coon Rapids Community Hospital Association and Glenwood Hills Hospital (Golden Valley). Builder: D\'Arcy Leck Const. Co. Designed for a 150-bed expansion, though what became Mercy Hospital II was a fresh approach. The original wing had an L-shape footprint with a 4-floor tower; overtime this has been lost in the many expansions typical of hospital in a growing suburban area.'),
(5692,E'5813 Hansen Rd',E'Edina',E'MN',55436,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1968',E'One of a pair of front walk-out ramblers that appear to be speaking to each other with their slightly askew siting.'),
(5693,E'5809 Hansen Rd',E'Edina',E'MN',55436,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1965',E'One of a pair of front walk-out ramblers that appear to be speaking to each other with their slightly askew siting.'),
(5694,E'3121 Pillsbury Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55408,NULL,NULL,E'Charles L. Horn Towers (3121)',E'S. C. Smiley and Associates',E'1969-71',E'Three 22-story towers with a combined 501-units of public housing for the elderly; built simultaneously. The complex is arranged around a large, sunken patio which is in-turn surrounded by an all-weather walk connecting the towers. Developed by the Minneapolis Housing & Redevelopment Authority (HRA), and named in 1969 after its chairman (from 1961-73, the HRA presented him with the model of the complex on his retirement); usually shortened to "Horn Towers." Such towers were popular in the 1960s-70s because the elderly mostly used elevators, zoning clauses allowed elderly residences to be bigger than others on a given site (since they have fewer cars and no children to attend local schools), and they were politically popular across party lines and among neighbors (especially as a stabilizing influence in areas of decline); their construction was also hastened by a major back-log of applicants (4-year waiting lists as of the construction of Horn Towers). Owner: Mpls Public Housing Auth; Builder: Bor-Son Const. Co. The sunken court in between the towers was eventually filled in and replaced with parking.'),
(5695,E'115 W 31st St',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55408,NULL,NULL,E'Charles L. Horn Towers (115)',E'S. C. Smiley and Associates',E'1969-71',E'Three 22-story towers with a combined 501-units of public housing for the elderly; built simultaneously. The complex is arranged around a large, sunken patio which is in-turn surrounded by an all-weather walk connecting the towers. Developed by the Minneapolis Housing & Redevelopment Authority (HRA), and named in 1969 after its chairman (from 1961-73, the HRA presented him with the model of the complex on his retirement); usually shortened to "Horn Towers." Such towers were popular in the 1960s-70s because the elderly mostly used elevators, zoning clauses allowed elderly residences to be bigger than others on a given site (since they have fewer cars and no children to attend local schools), and they were politically popular across party lines and among neighbors (especially as a stabilizing influence in areas of decline); their construction was also hastened by a major back-log of applicants (4-year waiting lists as of the construction of Horn Towers). Owner: Mpls Public Housing Auth; Builder: Bor-Son Const. Co. The sunken court in between the towers was eventually filled in and replaced with parking.'),
