(5697,E'26455 Muskey Ave S',E'Webster',E'WI',54893,NULL,NULL,E'Church of St. John the Baptist',E'Cerny Associates',E'c.1963',E'Art consultant: Frank T. Kacmarcik, Jr., who noted it was recognized for its religious architecture from the Liturgical Conference.'),
(5698,E'5401 Nicollet Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55419,NULL,NULL,E'Standard Oil Co. gas station',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Renovated, KKE Architects, 2004, to a restaurant space.'),
(5699,E'14949 62nd St N',E'Stillwater',E'MN',55082,NULL,NULL,E'Washington County Courthouse',E'Wold Associates',E'1969',E'Three-sectioned, $3.1M building. First section in 1969, courthouse section finished in 1975. Featured in a January 1976 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Andersen Corp. windows; Builder: Witcher Const. Co..'),
(5700,E'2525 Chicago Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55404,NULL,NULL,E'Children\'s Health Center and Hospital',E'Ellerbe Architects',E'1969-73',E'Originally a five-story T-shaped tower, broke ground in December 1969 with aim for a 13-month completion; beset by delays over financing the $6M budget that halted construction after excavation and foundation work, pushed opening to January 1973, and shrank the planned capacity from 200-beds to 160…then again to 130. The plan began in 1940, and was gradually developed over 15-years prior to groundbreaking, with a site selected between what were Mt. Sinai and Northwestern Hospitals. Featured in a March 1976 ad (in Progressive Architecture, then the biggest magazine on modernism) for Andersen Corp. windows; Builder: Bor-Son Const. Inc. The structure was designed to have additional floors added, and by a major addition in 2008 had 9-stories.'),
(5701,E'4350 Russell Ave N',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55412,NULL,NULL,E'Faith Baptist Church (add\'n)',E'Reese, Frank L.',E'1968',E'The original 1948-49 one-story brick building was more traditional in design (designed by W. Glen Wallace; cost: $75,000; built by Orville Madsen); the $220,000 addition transformed the structure into one that was much more modern: adding 17 classrooms, lounge-library, office and study, enlarging the fellowship hall, and gave the complex a new entrance and narthex; Builder (add\'n): Lyell C. Halverson.'),
(5702,E'26 Rocky Shore Dr',E'Iowa City',E'IA',52246,NULL,NULL,E'Albert Hood House II',E'Rapson, Ralph',E'1966',E'Almost as soon as Dr. Albert Hood had his award-winning dream house finished in Falcon Heights\' University Grove (1964), he took what ended up being his retirement-job at the University of Iowa. Undeterred, he had virtually the same house rebuilt on a new site here. He remained in the house until finally selling it in 2013.'),
(5703,E'2280 Water Tower Rd',E'Collegeville',E'MN',56321,NULL,NULL,E'St. Bede Hall (Saint John\'s Prep)',E'Michelson, Val',E'1961-62',E'1963 AIA MN Honor Award, received AIA MN\'s 25-Year Award (1991) awarded to both St. Bede and St. Michael Halls, which were planned in conjunction. St. Bede Hall is the academic building, initially consisting of large study halls, 12 classrooms, administrative and faculty offices, library, and recreation room; connected by underground tunnel to St. Michael Hall, split-level dormitory. Weber Center added in 1996; Meyer expansion for sciences in 2000; Middle School expansion in 2008. Valerius L. Michelson was a Russian-born architect who escaped during WW2 and was Marcel Breuer’s project manager and resident architect in Collegeville for 3 years; the design of the school was featured in his birthplace of Leningrad in 1965 as part of an architectural exhibit organized by the U.S. Information Agency in a cultural exchange program; the school was Michelson\'s first big commission after starting his own firm in St. Paul in 1960.'),
(5704,E'2240 Water Tower Rd',E'Collegeville',E'MN',56321,NULL,NULL,E'St. Michael Hall (Saint John\'s Prep)',E'Michelson, Val',E'1961-62',E'1963 AIA MN Honor Award, received AIA MN\'s 25-Year Award (1991) awarded to both St. Bede and St. Michael Halls, which were planned in conjunction. St. Bede Hall is the academic building, initially consisting of large study halls, 12 classrooms, administrative and faculty offices, library, and recreation room; connected by underground tunnel to St. Michael Hall, split-level dormitory. St. Michael Hall received a $5,450,000 renovation, completed in 2020. Valerius L. Michelson was a Russian-born architect who escaped during WW2 and was Marcel Breuer’s project manager and resident architect in Collegeville for 3 years; the design of the school was featured in his birthplace of Leningrad in 1965 as part of an architectural exhibit organized by the U.S. Information Agency in a cultural exchange program; the school was Michelson\'s first big commission after starting his own firm in St. Paul in 1960.'),
(5705,E'3630 Northome Rd',E'Deephaven',E'MN',55391,NULL,NULL,E'Ray Mithun Residence',E'Griffith, Newton',E'1961',E'Designed in a California style for the co-founder of advertising giant Campbell-Mithun; Ray Mithun wanted a house like those he admired in Palm Springs. The house has vaulted ceilings, deep eaves, walls of glass, and views of Lake Minnetonka. An errant article in the 2017 Star Tribune claimed the architect was a "Nute Griffith" from California (no such architect ever existed), however Newt Griffith was a successful Twin Cities architect whose own home was a 1962 Record House in Architectural Record (his career was cut short when he unexpectedly died in his sleep in 1968, age 44).'),
(5706,E'2623 107th Ln NW',E'Coon Rapids',E'MN',55433,NULL,NULL,E'L-Shape Rambler (Riverview Terrace Model)',E'Griffith, Newton',E'1965',E'One of 7 model homes that were specifically attributed: "designed and decorated by Newton Griffith, Peterson, Clark & Griffith, AIA (American Institute of Architects)" in advertising for developer Orrin Thompson\'s large suburban development; this promotion was likely due to his history as a successful Twin Cities architect whose own home was a 1962 Record House in Architectural Record (his career was cut short when he unexpectedly died in his sleep in 1968, age 44; his work for this developer was mentioned in the article about his death). While the homes were active models, the cul-de-sac was cut off by an octagonal hut, likely a sales office for the development. The development, which was built out from 1964 until approximately 1971, had over 18 styles available, it\'s unclear of Griffith had anything to do with any of the designs outside of these 7 model homes.'),
