(5713,E'111 E Kellogg Blvd',E'St Paul',E'MN',55101,NULL,NULL,E'Kellogg Square Apartments',E'Convention Center Associates',E'1969-72',E'Convention Center Architects & Engineers was a joint venture of Haarstick, Lundgren & Assoc., Grover Dimond Assoc., and Cerny Assoc.; Partners in charge: Louis Lundgren and Cecil Tammen. The 32-story apartment tower filled in the final space in the 40-year process of redeveloping the St. Paul riverfront along Kellogg Blvd, and the largest single project in the St. Paul Capital Centre development area. Developed by the St. Paul Housing & Redevelopment Authority with Los Angeles-based City Reconstruction Corp., the 466-unit, $13M luxury apartment project was downtown St. Paul\'s first residential high-rise and included 25 townhouse units (low-rise on the northwest side of the property), 600-car garage, recreation facilities, and retail space. Sited to place its narrow side facing the street, to allow river views for tenants on both sides as well as avoid blocking views from the adjacent First National Bank Building. Builder: Kraus-Anderson. Plans for the building were announced in the mid-1960s, but lawsuits over compensation to the previous owners of the land delayed it. Construction has a few unfortunate incidents: in June 1970, nearly 100ft of street and sidewalk on 4th St caved into the excavation due to soft clay, and in October 1970 a worker died from a fall. A strike by drivers for concrete companies caused delays and layoffs of construction workers as the project stalled for lack of materials. Name comes from the street, which was named for Minnesota politician and diplomat Frank B. Kellogg, who won the 1929 Nobel Peace Prize for negotiating the Kellogg–Briand Pact.'),
(5714,E'5120 Meadville St',E'Greenwood',E'MN',55331,NULL,NULL,E'Donald D. Stolz Residence',E'Bloomberg, Herbert',E'1964',E'Stolz was the longtime director of the Old Log Theater, hence his house was right by it. Bloomberg was a developer in Edina and Chanhassen who dabbled in design—best known for his Chanhassen Dinner Theater, but also designed the Old Log Theater down the street (5185 Meadville St) as well as the house across from it (5220 Meadville St); his one-off clients tended to be affluent people, and the houses he designed them often had many commonalities, several are present here: expensive finishes, avoiding traditional square/rectangular rooms, stone floors.'),
(5715,E'800 Main St',E'La Crosse',E'WI',54601,NULL,NULL,E'La Crosse Public Library',E'Hackner, Schroeder & Assoc.',E'1966-67',E'1968 Library Building Award of Merit winner (sponsored by the AIA, the American Library Association and the National Book Committee). The jury noted it was "An efficient plan, providing ample space for circulation."'),
(5716,E'900 11th Ave W',E'Spencer',E'IA',51301,NULL,NULL,E'Trinity Lutheran Church',E'Harold Spitznagel & Associates',E'1967-68',E'Primary program requirement was to enable the congregation to gather around the altar. It was desired that the seating arrangement gather the worshipping group as closely together as practicable around the pulpit, altar and font. Noted in an extensive feature profiling the practice of what was then called Spitznagel Partners Inc. in the January 1970 issue of the AIA Journal; the Sioux Falls-based firm was well regarded in the upper Midwest. The project was held up as an example of how, even in a tight budget, the firm managed to include art in some form—in this case and around the altar, where modest but effective art was chosen, highlighted by a cross suspended above the altar (designed by Palmer Eide). Construction cost: $267,545 ($16.75psf). At some point the top portion of the bold exterior form (originally all brick) was capped with wood in a matching color, lessening the effect somewhat but possibly as an inexpensive maintenance fix).'),
(5717,E'1060 3rd St SW',E'Huron',E'SD',57350,NULL,NULL,E'Agri-Horiculture Building',E'Harold Spitznagel & Associates',E'1965',E'Designed to combine agriculture and horticulture exhibits by the Huron office of the Sioux Falls-HQed firm; the head of that office, Frank Stitzel, was inspired to use a hexagonal design he saw on a fairground in Switzerland. The utilitarian structure is built of brick, steel and cement. The interior was designed with a central hexagonal exhibit room, 20ft in diameter, featuring mirrored walls and several clerestory windows above. The structure cost approximately $10,000.'),
(5718,E'1201 Northwest Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57104,NULL,NULL,E'Sioux Falls Arena',E'Harold Spitznagel & Associates',E'1960-62',E'Large, octagonal arena notable for its curved roof line and sloped seating for unobstructed viewing. Greatly expanded, but the original section is still prominent on the NE of the complex.'),
(5719,E'108 S Dakota Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57104,NULL,NULL,E'Northwestern Auto Bank',E'Harold Spitznagel & Associates',E'1965-66',E'Round bank featuring adjacent drive through lanes, built as a convenience supplement for the main branch headquarters on the same block (corner of 9th & Main St). Like many banks reacting to the post-War automotive boom, it had initially slapped two teller windows to the side of its old building but found it could not keep up with growing demand. The new auto-bank featured a cluster of 3 closed-circuit TV units for banking from vehicles (in a separate covered structure, connected under the parking lot), as well as in-lobby teller units in the round bank. Everything in the auto-bank was connected to the old bank via pneumatic tubes. Taking advantage of the sloped lot, the building appears as a one-story bank on the side of South Dakota Ave, but is two-floors on the alley side: the upper floor is the deck for the public driveway and auto-bank, while the alley-side has an entry for a garage as well as the bank\'s computer center. The walls are curved Pennsylvania sand cast brick, with woodwork in teak; the interior was designed with a round central skylight. Lobby floor was 6-inch hexagonal paving brick (extending out through the plaza area outside the main entrance). The opening was the subject of its own special section in the Argus-Leader newspaper (03/11/1966). Noted in an extensive feature profiling the practice of The Spitznagel Partners, Inc. in the January 1970 issue of the AIA Journal; the Sioux Falls-based firm was well regarded in the upper Midwest. The article noted the firm\'s commitment to implementing art into their designs, and for this project the center of the round bank featured a round fountain with bronze sculptures designed by noted California artist George Tsutakawa. Builder: S.F. Construction.'),
(5720,E'320 S 2nd Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57104,NULL,NULL,E'Sioux Falls Post Office & Federal Building',E'Harold Spitznagel & Associates',E'1965-66',E'Exterior faced in polished South Dakota Carnelian granite, quarried at Milbank and milled at granite-hub of Cold Springs, Minnesota. The 3-story (plus mechanical penthouse), $2,290,000 building was designed with 125,066sf. Interior featured tempo cream marble walls (from New Mexico). Mentioned in an extensive feature profiling the practice of what was then called Spitznagel Partners Inc. in the January 1970 issue of the AIA Journal; the Sioux Falls-based firm was well regarded in the upper Midwest.'),
(5721,E'225 S Main Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57104,NULL,NULL,E'Home Savings Association',E'Hugill, Blatherwick, Fritzel & Kroeger',E'1961-62',E'Most prominent feature of the 2-story, $630,000 structure is the metallic mesh "solar screen" that provides protection from the sun. Sign projects diagonally from the corner of the building.'),
(5722,E'2000 S Summit Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57105,NULL,NULL,E'Minnehaha Guidance Center',E'Hugill, Blatherwick, Fritzel & Kroeger',E'1960-61',E'Long, 2-story rectangular flat-roof structure fronted with a squarish single-story wing with accordion-style folded roof. Mental health clinic with diagnostic and therapeutic facilities. Previously named the Minnehaha County Mental Health Center before construction of the $263,695 new facility. South Dakota Governor Ralph Herseth attended the cornerstone laying in November 1960. Builder: Henry Carlson & Co.'),
(5723,E'2523 Portland Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55404,NULL,NULL,E'Ebenezer Tower Apartments',E'Thorsen & Thorshov',E'1969-70',E'Shared top-honors at the 1972 Design Awards for Nonprofit-Sponsored Low and Moderate Income Housing, sponsored biennially by the AIA, Nonprofit Housing Center Inc., and American Institute of Planners. The jury stated: "The design approach is an extremely successful one in the architectural treatment of a residential tower. Emphasis on the functions within the building, a straightforward use of materials and refined detailing achieve a strong landmark quality. Interior planning promotes interaction of tenants by the elimination of long corridors which are common in this type of housing. Community spaces, easily visible and accessible from floor lobbies, are strategically located and invite their use for a variety of activities. Unit plans reflect a high degree of skill and sensitivity." Notably, the top-two floors of the south face feature a large solarium room with a waffle slab ceiling. Owner: Ebeneezer Homes; Builder: Bor-Son Construction.'),
(5724,E'4300 98th St W',E'Bloomington',E'MN',55437,NULL,NULL,E'Bloomington Baptist Church',E'Bergstedt, Wahlberg, Bergquist Assoc.',E'1969',E'Founded in 1952 from the congregation at Richfield\'s Wooddale Baptist Church; original structure (the rectangular wing on the west) built in 1969. The next phase (1975-76), a $370,000 project adding 15,000sf, created the main worship center, fellowship hall, and offices and allowed the original wing to be converted into classrooms (by which time the firm was named Bergstedt Wahlberg Bergquist Rohkohl; Builder: Lyell Halverson). Congregation changed names to Hillside Church.'),
(5725,E'8400 France Ave S',E'Bloomington',E'MN',55431,NULL,NULL,E'St. Stephen Lutheran Church',E'Sovik, Mathre & Madson',E'1960-61',E'Original 1960-61 unit is the small northern section; Messiah Lutheran Church of Minneapolis provided the security for the initial $100,000 loan to finance the structure for the suburban young congregation (organized in 1959). Builder for the original section was Berglund & Johnson. The location, at the edge of the suburban housing boom in West Bloomington, led to a boom in membership: over 600 baptized members in 1961, over 1600 by 1965 (that was also very young, median age of 14 with only 1 funeral held in its first 6 years for an accident victim). The $225,000, 14,000sf second unit (1964-65), consisted of a parish hall and chapel, was added directly to the south. In 1974 a major addition added the new worship space to the immediate east of where the first two sections came together; it was designed with Bergstedt Wahlberg Bergquist Rohkohl, and the exterior of the original sections was extensively remodeled and does not appear like the original Sovik design. The 1975 National Interfaith Conference on Religion gave this a Merit Award. An addition in 2005 added a new section to the south, as well as to the northwest of the 1974 add\'n (connecting to the east wall of the original section of the structure).'),
(5726,E'4015 Auburn Dr',E'Minnetonka',E'MN',55305,NULL,NULL,E'Richard & Audrey Seelye Residence',E'Designers: Richard Seeyle & Robert William Sellen',E'1961',E'Sellen was a builder known designing unique European-style homes, but in this case the owner took it to an even greater level on the interior after being inspired by a trip to the continent. The Seelyes began finding photos and even attending movies in the hope of getting to see Swiss gables and balconies. Richard created a model of the home, then the couple began searching for materials from other buildings that were being demolished or remodeled. Richard was a craftsman, and he and Audrey enjoyed finding and reusing antique materials from other houses (openly admitting to finding things in trash piles of building demolitions or even the dump), as she noted: "If people would only keep their eyes open--so many beautiful things have been demolished." Builder Sellen saw the old 1880s St. Margaret\'s Academy (originally a mansion for W.W. McNair) being demolished and had the wreckers temporarily stop so the Seelyes could salvage it. From the McNair mansion, the couple took imported terra cotta European tiles (originally used in its kitchen; Richard installed them in the house himself), as ceramic tile for the fireplace, kitchen walls, and bath, as well as paneling and brass hardware. The living room fireplace was found in dump in La Cross, having been removed from a house that was converted to apartments. The main door was salvaged from the Oliver C. Wyman Mansion in Minneapolis (2500 Park Ave). Richard also designed and cut the walnut balcony rails based on designs he researched. House featured in the Minneapolis Tribune (09/09/1962). Richard Seelye was the president of Seelye Craftsmen, Inc., which did custom metal work for some of the other homes designed by Sellen. '),
(5727,E'530 Timberland Dr',E'Burnsville',E'MN',55337,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1963-64',E'The most eye-popping feature is the triangular fireplace opening outlined in stone on a stacked stone fireplace wall; also features a decorative geometric wood screen separating the entry hall from living room. First sale in 1967; designed with 3 bedrooms, game room, formal dining, family room, built-ins, etc. By 2021 real estate listing the interior was still in good shape.'),
(5728,E'1316 Tyrol Trail',E'Golden Valley',E'MN',55416,NULL,NULL,E'Verner Lundgren Residence',E'Unknown',E'1962',E'Set high on a sloping corner lot, taking advantage of the view of the pond to the SE. Significantly remodeled in 2005-07 (by SALA).'),
(5729,E'603 55th St W',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55419,NULL,NULL,E'Careview Home',E'Ellerbe Associates',E'1965',E'Nursing home developed by the Mount Olivet Lutheran Church, just north and adjoining their previously built Mount Olivet Home for Senior Citizens. The Careview Home design adapted Ellerbe\'s radial arrangement (developed at Rochester Methodist Hospital\'s test in the late-1950s and used in local hospitals) to allow constant observation between nursing stations (in the center of each unit) and patient rooms. The first phase had 150 beds with plans for 250 total beds at a cost of $1.5M. Originally had solar shades projecting from above each window (removed in late 2010s remodel).'),
