(5778,E'62 E Pleasant Lake Rd',E'North Oaks',E'MN',55127,NULL,NULL,E'House',E'Unknown',E'1964',E'Modern house in several forms clustered together; as of 2021 sale it was in a curious state of half-renovation; possibly set for demolition. Featured an interesting, double-height living room window with dramatic wood louvres. Sold in July 2021 and given a creatively bankrupt make-over to try and flip in November 2022 after all the unique charm (including louvers) stripped away.'),
(5779,E'3529 Owasso St',E'Shoreview',E'MN',55126,NULL,NULL,E'Midland Terrace Apartments',E'Dickey, Arthur H.',E'1968',E'Lakefront complex of ten 42-unit apartment buildings across 38-acres; the $5M project was developed by Midland Terrance, Inc. (run by Wally Johnson, who headed Kennel-Aire Mfg. Co.); builder: John R. Paulson Builder, Inc.; the plan was for the development to also include a small shopping center and medical clinic at the northern edge of the tract adjacent to County Road E. The exterior of the apartments were designed with cedar shake panels and concrete.'),
(5780,E'6303 Superior St',E'Duluth',E'MN',55804,NULL,NULL,E'Clifford D. Alexander Residence',E'Alexander, Clifford D.',E'1963',E'Architect\'s own house. The straightforward, modern flat-roof home uses clean lines and efficient use of space, sited on a wooded 1.3 acre lot. Clifford D. Alexander (1929-2020) was trained as a draftsman and worked for several architectural firms; he was a project architect for Duluth Architects Associated from 1952-66 before focusing his career on teaching at the University of Minnesota Duluth in Industrial Education. First listed on market in 2021.'),
(5781,E'5630 Lakeland Ave N',E'Crystal',E'MN',55429,NULL,NULL,E'Scandia Restaurant',E'Unknown',E'1961',E'Described as "The Twin City Area\'s Newest, Most Modern Restaurant" when it opened in October 1961, featuring food, cocktails, a large fireplace. Builder: Carlson-LaVine, Inc. Original sketch showed fewer windows; it was later converted to a used car sales center, with much more glass added to the highway front (though the extra glass works with the design).'),
(5782,E'657 2nd Ave N',E'Fargo',E'ND',58102,NULL,NULL,E'Federal Building and U.S. Post Office',E'Foss, Engelstad & Foss',E'1969',E'Large federal complex employing New Formalism in proportion and scale, the use of colonnades, arches, and smooth, black marble and white quartz aggregate cast-stone. The structure uses local Mankota stone and terrazzo in its public spaces. Listed on the National Register of Historic Places on June 4, 2021. The State Historical Society of North Dakota notes it remains the only known representation of late-1960s modernism of this scale, style, and quality in the city of Fargo.'),
(5783,E'1000 Northwest Ave',E'Sioux Falls',E'SD',57104,NULL,NULL,E'Good Samaritan Society Headquarters',E'Whitwam, Ward B.',E'1969-70',E'The national offices of the Evangelical Lutheran Good Samaritan Society had moved to Sioux Falls in 1963 from Fargo; at the time of construction of this central office building, they operated 136 facilities in 16 states (from North Dakota to New Mexico, and Indiana to Oregon, with the bulk in the Midwest). Builder: Christensen Corp. (Luverne, MN).'),
