(5921,E'2115 Stevens Ave',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55404,NULL,NULL,E'AAUW Clubhouse (add\'n)',E'McEnary & Krafft',E'1962',E'Modern addition to what was originally the Gale Mansion, a 1912 Renaissance Revival style structure faced in Bedford limestone and designed by Ernest Kennedy of Minneapolis. The owner, Edward Chanary Gale, was the son of Minneapolis pioneer real estate broker Samuel Gale. His wife, Sara Bell Pillsbury, was a daughter of Governor John S. Pillsbury. The Gales were leaders in the development of the Minneapolis Institute of Arts, which is located across the park. Edward and Sarah Gale both died in 1943; in 1947 the house was sold to the Minneapolis Branch of the American Association of University Women (AAUW), which was outgrowing its previous home at 310 Groveland. After some initial alterations to the mansion, the AAUW needed an auditorium space and built the modern addition on what was the garden. Listed on the National Registry of Historic Places on February 17, 1978 as part of the Washburn-Fair Oaks Mansion District'),
