(5997,E'1500 6th St NE',E'Minneapolis',E'MN',55413,NULL,NULL,E'Holland Elementary School',E'Peterson, Clark & Griffith',E'1968-69',E'Two-story, reinforced concrete structure with brick facade, rather austere and lifeless; architect Wilber B. Clark said new lighting, heating, and ventilation methods reduced the window requirements (fewer windows than most schools at the time). The school featured an inner court with a large, indoor carpeted playroom. Six intaglios were carved into the interior concrete block walls, based on original art rendered by the Holland pupils. The original proposal for the new site (Between 15th & 16th Aves NE and between 4th & 6th Sts NE) got pushback from the neighborhood, as it required the demolition of 24 homes, a grocery store, and would\'ve cut-off a portion of 5th St NE: residents were unhappy about "encroaching on an established neighborhood" and the nearby St Mary\'s Russian Orthodox Cathedral claimed that its position 100yds away would cause a disruption of worship services. The Holland and Sheridan Schools PTA (the schools were to be combined) supported the new site, and characterized opposition as older residents. The site was ultimately selected, with some adjustments that kept it between 5th & 6th Sts NE (eliminating the need to block 5th) and bringing it further north on the block (eliminating 25 houses), closer to St. Mary\'s. The plan approved by the Minneapolis School Board in fall 1967 was for 14 classrooms, 2 kindergarten rooms, with a capacity of 520 students. From the sketches, the design was a fairly plain rectangular building from the start. School opened in February 1969. Plaque outside the building memorializes the "Holland School 1886" which was previously located at 17th Ave NE and Washington Ave (replaced with The Holland Hi-Rise public housing tower).'),
